<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Deposed First Prime Minister Prince Norodom
Ranariddh will give back the area under the control of the forces
loyal to him, according to a statement received here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the four-point statement released Friday, Ranariddh said
that he fully supports King Norodom Sihanouk's ceasefire proposal.
</P>
<P>
In addition to declaring a unilateral ceasefire, he said, he
will give back the area under the control of the troops loyal to
him. (Cambodia-Ranariddh)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KATHMANDU -- The three-member new government of Nepal led by
Girija Prasad Koirala obtained a vote of confidence Saturday
afternoon with a comfortable majority in the Lower House of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The government garnered 144 votes in the 205-seat Lower House,
41 more than needed to win a vote of confidence, as the main
opposition Communist Party of Nepal and the newly-formed National
Democratic Party both threw their weight behind Koirala as they
had promised. (Nepal-Government-Vote)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The body of Pol Pot, former leader of the Khmer
Rouge, was cremated Saturday in a northern Cambodian village three
kilometers from the Thai border.
</P>
<P>
Local television showed that the body was put in a wooden
coffin, which was set alight when the simple ceremony began at
about 0230 GMT Saturday morning. (Thailand-Pol Pot Cremation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Several hundred Palestinian protesters clashed
with Israeli soldiers Saturday in East Jerusalem, but there was no
reports of casualties so far.
</P>
<P>
The clash took place in Salah A-Deen Street, when the
palestinians are protesting for the Palestinian prisoners detained
in Israeli jails on the Palestinian prisoners Day Saturday.
(Israel-Clash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Leaders from 34 countries opened their Second
Summit of the Americas Saturday morning, trying to bolster a
proposed new free trade area.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was chaired by host Chilean President Eduardo Frei,
and former host U.S. President Bill Clinton addressed the opening
of the meeting on the major achievements since last summit.
</P>
<P>
As well as the proposed Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA),
the participants will discuss education and other topics,
including building wealth through economic integration and trade,
and rejecting poverty amid growing prosperity.
(Santiago-Summit-Open) 
</P>
</TEXT>
