<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unionist Party Wins Support for N.Irish Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's Ulster Unionist
Party (UUP), the major Protestant party, voted on Saturday to give
their backing for a "yes" vote in next month's referendum on the
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the 800-strong ruling council of the UUP held
in Belfast, 540 voted for and 210 voted against the accord which
was struck last weekend by the main Protestant and Roman Catholic
parties in the province.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, UUP leader David Trimble said his party
still had concerns over parts of the agreement, but it opened the
path to a new era.
</P>
<P>
"We too are making compromises for the greater good...The door
is open for the rest of the community to come through it with us."
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be put to a referendum in both Northern
Ireland and the Irish Republic on May 22.
</P>
<P>
Trimble acknowledged fears expressed by many Protestant
Unionists that the peace deal will allow Sinn Fein leaders to hold
political office while its IRA guerrilla wing holds on to its
guns.
</P>
<P>
"I now ask the IRA and Sinn Fein: Are they prepared to finally
and irrevocably renounce violence?" Trimble said after the vote.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams told a meeting of
his party in Dublin, the Irish Republic, that a final assessment
on the peace agreement would be given at a special Sinn Fein
conference to be held within a month.
</P>
<P>
But he added that last week's accord "has the potential to
redefine the relationships between these two islands".
</P>
<P>
Adams also congratulated UUP leader Trimble for winning the
vote within his party in Belfast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
