<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British PM in Saudi Arabia on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 18 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair arrived in Jeddah, the Red Sea port city of Saudi Arabia,
on Saturday on the second leg of his first Middle East tour aimed
at "kicking start" the stalled Arab-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Press Agency monitored here reported that during his
stopover in Jeddah, Blair will discuss with Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz and Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz means of
reviving the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
Their talks will also cover the situation in the Gulf region,
the developments of ties between Gulf Arab states and Iran, and
the Israeli-proposed conditional withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
A diplomat from the British Embassy in Saudi Arabia said Blair
is keen to know the Saudi viewpoint over ways to reinvigorate the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister, who flew in from Egypt, is also
scheduled to travel on to Jordan, Israel and the Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
Blair and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak agreed Friday that
additional efforts should be made to build confidence among
parties concerned in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Britain is reportedly deeply worried about the freezing of the
peace process and calls on Israel to abide by the agreements it
signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Saudi newspapers commented Saturday that Blair's visit to the
kingdom is of vital importance because it will provide a good
opportunity for both sides to exchange views on issues of mutual
concern.
</P>
<P>
Blair's talks with Saudi leaders are also expected to focus on
means to increase bilateral trade and the case of two British
nurses held in Saudi jail since December 1996 for murdering an
Australian colleague, a spokesman for Blair said Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
