<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Summit of Americas Opens in Santiago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the 34 countries in
the west hemisphere opened their Second Summit of Americas here
Saturday, joining hands to give a new push to the proposed
ambitious Free Trade Area of Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
The meeting is held at the conference hall of the Sheraton
Hotel here and chaired by the host Chilean President Eduardo Frei.
The previous host, U.S. President made speech at the beginning of
the meeting, summarizing major achievements in the four years
since the last summit. President Frei also made remarks outlining
a broad agenda for the 2-day Santiago Summit.
</P>
<P>
Following a brief opening session, which lasted for about 30
minutes, the 34 leaders and their ministers entered close-door
working discussions.
</P>
<P>
There are four topics on the Santiago summit's agenda. The
participants will focus their most discussions on education, which
is to form a basket itself. The others baskets include Making
Democracy Relevant, Enjoying the Fruits of Freedom, Building Our
Wealth through Economic Integration and Trade, Rejecting Poverty
Amid Growing Prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Besides, in light with the reguest of the Caribbean Prime
Ministers, the issue of social security would be also discussed.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Summit, U.S. President Bill Clinton paid a two-
day state visit to Chile. A number of bilateral agreements on
expanding trade, enhancing education and environment protection
were reached or signed between Chile and the U.S., Chile and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean Minister of Foreign Affairs, Jose Miguel Insulza
said that the recently signed bilateral agreements are "a good
sign of the Second Summit".
</P>
<P>
The First Summit of Americas was held in Miami of the United
States in December 1994. The meeting set the goal of establishing
the FTAA by 2005 in the hemisphere and adopted a plan of actions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Urges Angolan Parties to Move on Toward Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- an OAU delegation to Angola
calls for continued vigilance on the part of all the peace-loving
forces to avoid the recurrence of the 1992 events that led to the
reversal of the peace process in the country.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) here Saturday said the OAU mission to Angola led by
Assistant Secretary General in charge of political affairs
Ambassador Daniel Antonio has made the call in a statement after
its five-day visit to Angola.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, the OAU delegation had "productive, frank"
meetings will all parties to the Lusaka peace process, which have
enabled it "to fully appreciate the concerns of the government
and the United Nations regarding the attainment of the few
remaining tasks contained in the implementation program.''
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, ''the remaining talks have to do
with the extension of state administration to the remaining
areas, particularly the five sensitive regions of Sautar, Andulo,
Bailundo, Nharea and Mungo and also the demilitarization of the
remaining residual forces of UNITA (National Union for Total
Independence of Angola).''
</P>
<P>
The statement said the OAU delegation while welcoming the
progress that has been achieved to date in the implementation of
the peace process, is optimistic that the remaining tasks will be
implemented by the new agreed deadline of april 25, 1998.
</P>
<P>
''Realizing that the continued violation of the sanctions
regime imposed by the U.N. Security Council on UNITA by some
states could jeopardize the entire peace process, the OAU
delegation appeals to the international community to scrupulously
abide by the terms of the sanctions regime,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The OAU mission also appeals to UNITA to move without any
further delay or hindrance to meet the remaining tasks, so that
the people of Angola can at long last be allowed to have peace,
and stability and exert all their energies toward the social and
economic development of their country.
</P>
<P>
''The OAU delegation further observes the need for the
international community to continue to demonstrate its solidarity
with the people of Angola as they move into the more difficult
phase of national reconstruction, rehabilitation and
development,'' the statement said, adding that ''in that regard,
it calls for more resources to be directed toward de-mining
activities, the rehabilitation and assistance of mine victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe: Tobacco Sales Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco sales in Zimbabwe has
dropped by about 58 percent in the first 12 days of the marketing
season as against last year, the Zimbabwean Tobacco Association
(ZTA) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Over 7.3 million kilograms of tobacco at an average price of
1.33 U.S. Dollars per kilogram have been sold by end of the week,
10 million kilograms less than the same period last year, ZTA
Market Information Director Pat Davis told the Zimbabwean News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
"The main reason for such a drop in sales is because a lot of
growers have canceled bookings or rejecting some of the prices,"
said Davis.
</P>
<P>
During the first 12 sale days of last year, prices averaged
2.07 U.S. Dollars per kilogram, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the devaluation of the local currency
this year, prices of tobacco have remained low and farmers have
been withholding their crop until prices turn firm later in the
season.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the beginning of the marketing season on
March 31, there has not been much improvement and competition is
still on the weak side with offerings tending to be on the lower
quality.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is the country's biggest foreign currency earner. A
total of about 220 million kilograms was expected to be sold this
year, earning the country over 500 million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
