<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saddam Attends Volunteers' Military Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on
Saturday attended an over-six-hour-long volunteers' military
parade held at the Grand Festivities' Square in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
More than 120,000 out of 3 million volunteers including men
and women from Baghdad and other Iraqi provinces took part in the
parade, according to the official Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Iraq started military training of volunteers from early
February this year amid the Iraq-U.N. weapons inspection crisis,
during which the United States and Britain threatened to launch
military strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
With the signing of the memorandum of understanding February 23
by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Iraq on opening Iraqi
presidential sites to U.N. inspections, the crisis was defused
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States and Britain still maintain a
formidable force in the Gulf region on the ground that they want
to ensure smooth implementation of the Iraq-U.N. accord.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's military parade, dubbed Gallantry Day, was also
attended by officials of the ruling Baath Party and the
government, and heads of Arab and foreign diplomatic missions in
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Popularize Use of Mosquito-nets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Health of
Ethiopia says Saturday that it has drawn up a strategy to
popularize the use of mosquito-nets in an effort to prevent the
effects of malaria.
</P>
<P>
Tarekegne Abosse, team leader of malaria and other
vector-borne diseases of the ministry told local journalists here
that preparations are underway to give orientations on the proper
use of mosquito-nets to groups of societies residing in areas
prone to malaria epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Tarekegne noted that his ministry has plans to distribute
about 33,000 mosquito-nets to people in selected areas free and
offer technical trainings about the proper utilization of the
items, saying that his ministry has also devised strategies
through which the public could buy mosquito-nets at reasonable
prices.
</P>
<P>
He urged the private sector to engage in the production of
mosquito-nets so that the public could get the items at fair
prices.
</P>
<P>
Tarekegne said the United Nations Children's Fund (Unicef) has
drafted plans enabling children under the age of five in malaria
ridden parts of Africa to develop the culture of using
mosquito-nets until the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) has donated 15,000
mosquito-nets to the ministry, according to Tarekegne.
</P>
<P>
Over 70 percent of Ethiopia's total land is said to be ideal
places for breeding mosquitos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Raps UNSCOM for Leaking Information to Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 18 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi spokesman on Saturday
criticised the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq
for leaking information and releasing statements about the
commission's activities in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The commission's "conduct contradicts its commitments to the
U.N. which forbids its employees to release any statement to the
media while they are on the job unless permitted to do so," said
the spokesman of the Iraqi Ministry of Information and Culture.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, who was not named, was referring to statements of
UNSCOM Deputy Chairman Charles Duelfer published in the New York
Times newspaper Wednesday concerning Iraqi presidential sites,
which were suspected of hiding secretive weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
Duelfer had leaked part of a report on the outcome of UNSCOM
team's inspections to these sites, which should be submitted to the
U.N. chief, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He leveled the same charge against UNSCOM Chairman Richard
Butler, who he said also had leaked to the same newspaper on April
17 part of his half-yearly report to be submitted to the U.N.
chief even before the Security Council has a chance to read it.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the inspections of presidential sites proved
that both British and U.S. administrations as well as UNSCOM
leaders were not telling the truth, because the arms inspectors
found no banned weapons or materials in the sites.
</P>
<P>
The eight sites, previously declared "off-limits," were
inspected by a special group of senior U.N. diplomats and arms
experts from March 26 to April 2, in accordance with a deal
stricken by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan with Iraq government
on February 23.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of inspections "has disappointed the liers who
ordered their representatives in the Special Commission to launch
a propaganda campaign against Iraq and the diplomatic efforts
exerted by the U.N. to implement Security Council resolutions,"
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"The anti-Iraq U.S. and British campaign only aims at
diverting attention from Iraq's demand to implement paragraph 22
of resolution 687 which provides for the lifting of the embargo
now that Iraq has complied with all its obligations toward
Security Council resolutions," he added.
</P>
<P>
The crippling U.N. sanctions against Iraq imposed since its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990 can be lifted only after UNSCOM
certifies that Iraq has eliminated all prohibited weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
