<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean President Urges for Joint Efforts for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- While opening the Second Summit
of Americas here Saturday, Chilean President Eduardo Frei
Ruiz-Tagle called on the other 33 nations of the west hemisphere
to join hands in fighting against social diseases and for social
development.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the opening meeting of the 2-day summit,
President Frei said, individual nations "can no longer formulate
their policies without taking into account of their place in a
regional and global framework. The era of autarkies has ended."
</P>
<P>
Standing alone, the Chilean leader added, it is very difficult
to "grapple with challenges such as drug trafficking, organized
crime or the spread of infectious diseases." "Even issues which
have traditionally been considered domestic in scope, such as
social injustice, education, the modernization of the State and
the fight against corruption, have taken on international
dimensions. Global problems cannoted be solved with unilateral
policies," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The 34 leaders of the west hemisphere has set forth a broad and
busy agenda for the meeting. However, on the top of the agenda is
the topic of education.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot hope to break down the barriers that divide social
groups nor achieve sustainable economic growth as a region without
effectively educating our people," Frei noted.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot participate in a competitive and globalized world
if our people are not capable of applying the spectacular
scientific and technical advances of our era. Education, in farms
and factories as well as in schools and universities, is the best
means of providing all of our citizens with the chance to improve
their own lives," the President explained.
</P>
<P>
Frei also called on the participating countries to develop
active science and technology policies, to support the educational
reform processes and to strengthen cooperation in the field of
education.
</P>
<P>
Talking about pushing forward the integration and liberalization
of trade and investment, the Chilean leader said, Chile has "an
enormous interest" in establishing clear and stable rules for its
commerce with the rest of the countries of the Americas. In a
globalized world, the well-being of the countries is linked to the
liberalization of commerce, and thus "we must continue to resist
protectionism. In so doing, we must ensure that the rhetoric of
free trade is translated into concrete action," he underlined.
</P>
</TEXT>
