<HEADLINE> 10 Palestinians Injured in East Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Ten Palestinian protesters were
injured and 20 others arrested Saturday in East Jerusalem during
clashes with Israeli soldiers while marking the Palestinian
Prisoners Day.
</P>
<P>
The injured include Hatem Abdel Qader and Ahmad Batsh, two
members of the Palestinian Council, according to the Palestinian
police.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred Palestinians staged a protest Saturday in
Salah A-Deen Street of the Old City in East Jerusalem, calling on
Israel to release all Palestinians held in Israeli jails. The
demonstration led to clashes with Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers and security forces closed off the street to
prevent the situation there from further worsening and put East
Jerusalem under tight security control for fear of unrest.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrations organized by the Palestinian Prisoners Society
were also held Saturday in the West Bank cities of Jenin,
Tulkarem, and Qalqilya. There were no reports of clash from these
cities so far.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side estimated that a total of 3,000
Palestinians are being held in Israeli jails either under
administrative detention without charges or under criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Israeli Defense Force released Ahmed
Katamesh, 45, leader of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine. Katamesh was arrested on September 1, 1992 and
transferred to administrative detention in october 1993.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's protest was the first held this year by Palestinians
in East Jerusalem, which Israel claimed as part of its sole
capital while Palestinians want as capital of their future state.
</P>
</TEXT>
