<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Acquires 40 Percent Shares of Foreign Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The ambitious Angolan National
Petroleum Corporation has bought 40 percent of the shares of the
Oil Company of Sao Tome and Principe.
</P>
<P>
It did so in a way of increasing its investment into this
island country in the Gulf of Guinea, which has recently found a
rich under sea oil field, the official Angolan News Agency
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Besides the petroleum corporation, other businesses of Angola
also seek to invest in Sao Tome and Principe, mainly in the
fields of marine shipping, agriculture and tourism, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Erhack Corporation, a U.S. company, has recently discovered a
big oil field in the waters of the Sao Tome and Principe, which
is similar to those in Alaska in terms of reserves and quality.
This has prompted Angola's companies to invest in this island
country.
</P>
<P>
Like Angola, many foreign companies from Portugal, the United
States, and France which have swarmed to invest in this island
state in the wake of the discovery.
</P>
<P>
At present, Sao Tome and Principe has to import all its
petroleum products from Angola, which is the second largest oil
producer in sub-Sahara.
</P>
<P>
The two Portuguese-speaking countries enjoy close relations in
both politics and economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
