<HEADLINE> 60 Turks Detained in Protest Against Scarf Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A total of 60 protesters have been
taken into custody in a protest against the government's ban on
scarf-wearing in Turkey's southeastern province of Bingol, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chanting anti-secular slogans, hundreds of Muslims held a
rally in Solhan county late Friday after their prayers in mosque,
demanding the government remove the ban on scarf-wearing of female
civil workers and girl students.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, armed with sticks and stones, tried to break
into the government building and clashed with riot police sent to
disperse the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Several demonstrators and policemen suffered injuries in the
clash and were rushed to a nearby hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Bingol Governor Suleyman Kamci was quoted as saying that the
anti-government protest is illegal because it did not get the
approval of the provincial government beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Turkish government and local authorities have issued
regulations banning female civil workers and girl students from
wearing scarf in the offices and on the campus.
</P>
<P>
Conservative Muslims have voiced strong opposition to the
regulations, accusing them of constituting a violation of
citizen's religious freedom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
