<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief on Asian Financial Crisis at ECOSOC's High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The interchange on global
financial integration and development between the diplomatic,
financial and developmental cooperation communities from the more
than twenty countries will enrich the whole world, UN
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the special high-level meeting on global financial
integration and development initiated by the UN Social and
Economic Council(ECOSOC), the Secretary-General said the meeting
would help breaking the more strait-jacketed ways of thinking and
move the international community forward in the search of common
good, in the eradication of poverty and the creation of conditions
of stability and predictability.
</P>
<P>
Annan said finance was central to the development process, but
development finance was also an area where, in recent years, the
thinking had changed fundamentally; and where, at the same time,
dramatic development had taken place. There was now universal
recognition of the developmental role of private international
capital flows, which had brought with them tremendous benefits.
</P>
<P>
There were three main areas of concern in the implementation of
the recent crisis in Asia, he said. First and foremost, was the
situation of the crisis countries themselves.
</P>
<P>
"I think we are all preoccupied by the harsh toll these crises
impose in an entire citizenry", he said. Those hardest hit were
usually the most vulnerable Job seekers who had migrated during
the good times; the poor who could no longer pay for the higher
priced basic necessities; those groups which were employed in the
least organized sectors of the economy. Beyond that was the
continuing threat of social strife, breakdown of law and order and
loss of self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
Another major area fo concern, he said, was that the precise
impact of the Asian crisis could not be separated from all other
independent development affecting the world economy. Yet it was
becoming increasingly apparent that other developing and
transition countries would be affected more severely by the crisis
than their developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"In other words, the collateral damage is greater in developing
countries than elsewhere," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Pledges to Win "Fast Track" to Push FTAA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- While addressing the opening
session of the Second Summit of Americas here Saturday, U.S.
President Bill Clinton vowed to win the "fast track" legislation
to push forward the process for the Free Trade Area of Americas
(FTAA).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. leader reassured the U.S. government's commitment to
the free trade area of Americas which will be "in the fast lane of
our concerns."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also outlined some remarkable achievements in the last
three and a half years since the Miami Summit in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
The economy of the region has grown 15 percent. Last year,
average growth was five percent, and inflation was the lowest in
50 years. Chile and Uruguay have set the standard for poverty
reduction and fiscal responsibility. Brazil and Argentina have
slowed inflation to a crawl. Mexico has overcome adversity,
transformed its economy, broadened its democracy, Clinton noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bolivia has attracted new foreign investments and
Venezuela's Apertura program is drawing investment to develop its
energy resources. Peru and Ecuador, with a little help from their
friends, are working toward a peaceful end to their protracted
border disputes. After some years of strife, Central America is
well on the way to achieving its long-held vision of democracy and
integration and growth. Caribbean nations are joining forces to
expand their economies and to defend their shores against drugs
and crime, as the President noted.
</P>
<P>
"The Miami Summit was a watershed in the history of our
hemisphere as the leaders of free people embraced a common vision
of the future and a common strategy for achieving it. The journey
from Miami to Santiago has been filled with progress toward our
goals," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"Four years ago at Miami, we planted the seed of a new
partnership for a new century. Now we can and must do what is
necessary for that seed to grow -- to grow in freedom and
opportunity and cooperation," the U.S President concluded.
</P>
<P>
In order to review progress since the Miami Summit, a 193-page
report entitled "Words into Deeds" was released here today, which
is focused on implementation of the decisions reached at the 1994
Miami Summit of the Americas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
