<HEADLINE> 2nd Nigerian Party Adopts Abacha as Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Party of Nigeria
(DPN) Saturday adopted head of the military government General
Sani Abacha as its sole candidate for the August 1 presidential
election. It is the second of Nigeria's five political parties to
do so.
</P>
<P>
Before DPN, Nigeria's largest party, the United Nigeria
Congress Party (UNCP) has at its national convention in Kaduna
Thursday adopted General Abacha as its sole flagbearer in the
coming election.
</P>
<P>
The motion to adopt Abacha as the DPN's candidate was moved by
the party's national chairman Alhaji Saleh Hassan, at a national
convention held in Nigeria's oil industry center Port Harcourt in
the south.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the British Broadcasting Corporation
(BBC), the motion was put to voice vote and the delegates
responded with a roar of "yes." There was no dissident voice.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the nomination, the party amended its
constitution to allow Abacha to contest on the party's platform.
The constitution formerly restricted candidacy to only
card-carrying members.
</P>
<P>
By tomorrow, when their national conventions end, the three
other parties, the National Center Party of Nigeria, the
Grass-roots Democratic Movement (GDM) and the Congress for
National Consensus Party are also expected to adopt Abacha as
their presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
The only problem will probably come from the GMD, as both
Mohammed Yusurf and Tunji Braithweaite, the only two persons that
have declared their interest to contest for the presidency have
expressed their wish to do so on the platform of the GMD.
</P>
<P>
Should General Abacha become the sole presidential candidate,
the next question arising will be whether there is need for a
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In fact, there has been a suggestion from some quarter of the
politicians that if the five parties adopt Abacha as their
consensus candidate, there will be no need for the presidential
election, which will then be replaced by a national referendum.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled presidential election in August was part of
General Sani Abacha transition to civil rule program announced in
1995, by which he promised to give power to an elected civilian
government in October this year.
</P>
<P>
He has been so far silent on the issue of whether he will run
or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
