<HEADLINE> Zambia Wants No War on Neighbors: Chiluba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba said
Saturday that Zambia doesn't want to wage war against its
neighbors, the Zambian National Broadcasting Corporation (ZNBC)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The country is too "preoccupied" with economic reforms that it
doesn't want to wage war against its neighbors, ZNBC quoted
Chiluba as saying here.
</P>
<P>
While briefing Daniel Antonio, visiting Assistant
Secretary-General for political affairs of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), Chiluba further explained that Zambia has no
capacity or the means to start antagonizing its neighbors in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president said that his country is committed to
peace "although we may be provoked, we shall not retaliate
because we want peace."
</P>
<P>
He further pointed out that Zambia wants peace with Angola
"not out of fear."
</P>
<P>
These remarks follow Luanda's accusations that Zambia has
been involved in supplying arms to Angola's former rebel
movement, the National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA).
</P>
<P>
And the Angolan ambassador to Zambia gave a strong warning at
a news briefing here in March that Zambia may face a military
intervention if its territory continues to be used for airlifting
arms supplies to UNITA.
</P>
<P>
In response to the earlier accusations which have been denied
by the Zambian side, Chiluba told the OAU envoy that his
government has imposed a ban on all airports in the country when
it started hearing that suspected planes were landing and taking
off from the country's unknown airports.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba reiterated that Zambia is committed to the Lusaka
Peace Protocol signed in 1994 between UNITA and the Angolan
government.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Zambia wants peace with its neighbors
including Angola, because if any country in Africa is
destabilized it is the whole Africa which is destabilized.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba noted that there is a possibility for the two
countries to be friendly and live as brothers as it has been in
the past.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Antonio thanked Zambia for its efforts to
host and take care of 32,000 refugees from surrounding countries.
</P>
<P>
The OAU envoy arrived in Lusaka Thursday on a mission to
acquaint himself with the political and economic development in
the member countries and, as for Angola, to monitor the
implementation of the Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Antonio visited the Zambian-Angolan border areas.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Lusaka, Antonio has been to Namibia and
Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
