<HEADLINE> Zanzibar to Plant More Clove Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar will embark on a
massive campaign to plant clove trees next week, reports reaching
here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The planting of new clove trees is part of an afforestation
campaign of the isles in the Indian Ocean, the reports quoted
Brigadier General Adam Mwakanjuki, the Zanzibar Minister for
Agriculture, Livestock and Natural Resources, as saying.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 trees are expected to be planted on the twin
islands of Zanzibar, with half on on the Unguja island and the
other half on the Pemba island to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the campaign will be formerly
launched by Chairman of the National Environmental Management
Council Reginald Mengi.
</P>
<P>
Mwakanjuki said that the campaign is part of the isles'
environmental conservation program, as felling of trees to obtain
firewood and building materials has been rampant.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the problem, the reports said, the government
will also launch a massive education and publicity campaign to
make the public aware of the importance of environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
Clove exports, which used to be the isles' principal foreign
exchange earner, have been in decline for more than a decade
following the fall of prices in the world market. In recent
years, tourism has become the major foreign exchange earner.
</P>
</TEXT>
