<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Two Years on, Tears Still Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 18 (Xinhua) -- When Sofi Said was pulled out from
beneath ruins and corpses after an Israeli bomb hit the shelter
she and other villagers were hiding two years ago today, she was
thought to be dead.
</P>
<P>
Shrapnels of the Israeli bomb that had killed her husband,
Ahmad Ibrahim, and her 22-year-old daughter, Irham, and more than
100 others instantly in Gana village in south Lebanon, had ripped
into her waist and knocked her off.
</P>
<P>
"I was unconscious and full of blood. After dragging me out,
the rescuers touched my pulse and were surprised to find I was
still alive," said Sofi, who was 55 at the time.
</P>
<P>
She was immediately taken to a hospital in Sidon, Lebanon's
biggest southern coastal city, for emergency treatment, then
transferred to the country's most famous hospital affiliated to
the American University of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Her injuries were so severe that she had two operations and was
confined in the hospital for two months. But 107 people, including
her husband and daughter, died their tragic deaths in the
notorious Gana massacre that day - April 18, 1996.
</P>
<P>
It has always been full of pain and fear when Sofi forced her
memory to the day. "Life for me is meaningless since I lost my
husband and my dear daughter," she cried, "How can I live without
them?
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of villagers of Gana and neighboring villages were
seeking shelter in the conference hall of the Fijian contingent of
the United Nations Interim Forces in Lebanon (UNFIL), to escape
Israeli air raids and artillery bombardment.
</P>
<P>
"We had thought the U.N. forces' camps should be safe and
Israelis would never attack them. But they did," Sofi said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops launched military offensive dubbed Grapes of
Wrath on April 13, 1996 in retaliation for Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks, and air-raided on April 18 the Fijian
contingent compound in Qana, just north of the Israeli self-styled
security zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the 1,200-square-kilometer border enclave in
south Lebanon in 1985 after two invasions, with the claimed aim of
protecting its northern settlements from guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 107 Lebanese civilians killed in the raid,
more than 200 others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
"My daughter was only 22 when she died. She had just finished
her study in the high school and prepared to go to university.
But ...," she couldn't continue, tears running down her face.
</P>
<P>
Sofi is now living with her only son to accompany her beloved
husband and daughter, who were buried on the slope leading to the
massacre site. Two years on, she has difficulty to sleep, feels
weak and depressed, and takes a variety of medicines to help fight
the daily nightmare of the bloody killing.
</P>
<P>
She was extremely skeptical about a possible Israeli withdrawal
from south Lebanon. "Following the massacre, they (Israelis)
announced they wanted to pull out. But until now, nothing
happened," she said.
</P>
<P>
"How can you believe in the words of the killers?" she asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
