<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Ends Military Training of Volunteers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq signaled the conclusion of
its over-two-month-long military training of volunteers with a
parade that lasted more than six hours Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to reporters after the parade, dubbed Gallantry
Day, Iraqi Minister of Culture and Information Hammam Abdul-Khaliq
described the it as a "coronation" to the training sessions in
response to President Saddam Hussein's call for taking up arms
against a possible foreign invasion.
</P>
<P>
More than 120,000 out of 3 million volunteers including men and
women from Baghdad and other provinces took part in the parade,
which was also attended by Saddam and officials of the ruling
Baath Party.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister said "the parade is a message sent by the
great Iraqi people to the U.S. and British troops and armed forces
in the Gulf region to show that the Iraqis are ready, at any time,
to defend their country and to stand against any evil attempt to
jeopardize Iraq's integrity and sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
Iraq started military training of volunteers from early
February this year amid the Iraq-U.N. weapons inspection crisis,
during which the United States and Britain threatened to launch
air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
After the crisis was defused with the signing of an accord by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Iraq late February, the
United States and Britain keep their formidable forces in the
region to "ensure smooth execution of the accord."
</P>
<P>
On the relationship between Iraq and the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction, the minister said that Iraq is awaiting the
results of the Security Council's meetings at the end of this
month, which will review the sanctions imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-imposed sanctions on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait can not be lifted unless UNSCOM verifies that Iraq is free
of weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
