<HEADLINE> Bartoli Wins World Cup Cycling Race in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Michele
Bartoli took on Sunday the title of the 84th Liege-Bastogne-Liege
cycling race that was also a World Cup event, the fourth on this
year's circuit.
</P>
<P>
The Italian rider clocked six hours 38 minutes 31 seconds over
the 265.5-kilometer race. Second place went to Laurent Jalabert
of France, followed by Rodolfo Massi also from Italy.
</P>
<P>
Jalabert was 1:06 adrift from the winner.
</P>
<P>
Bartoli launched his final attack with some 14 kilometers left
by overtaking early leader and 1994 Liege World Cup winner Evgeni
Berzin of Russia.
</P>
<P>
He then led the remaining race in front of the immediate
chasing pack of six which was soon joined by Berzin who simply
faded in the end of the one-day race.
</P>
<P>
Bartoli, fifth place finisher of last Wednesday's non-classic
cycling race from Charleroi to Huy also in Belgium, plucked out
all in him in the final climb of a 15-percent ascent toward the
finish.
</P>
<P>
He pounded his fist forward for a triumphant gesture after he
looked back to make sure that no one was within real challenging
distance.
</P>
<P>
Home favorite Frank Vandenbroucke could not hold on to the
final kick only to finish outside the top five. The Belgian won
the Paris-Nice and Gent-Wevelgem cycling races earlier this season
and was ranked third by the International Cycling Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
