<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Begins New Round Of Infrastructure Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- To stimulate demand and keep its
economy on track, China is starting a massive infrastructure
project estimated to cost 750 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts here have pointed out that the investment,
approximately 2 trillion yuan each year for the next three years,
will have a profound effect on economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The central government has increased this year's spending on
railways to 45 billion yuan from 38.9 billion yuan and work on 9
new railways is expected to begin this year. Railway Ministry
sources say that total spending could run as high as 250 billion
yuan from now to the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
China has also increased spending on other infrastructure like
expressways, water conservation facilities, urban utilities, and
environmental protection, according to a State Development
Planning Commission official, who predicts that total spending
will exceeds one trillion yuan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
To boost domestic spending, the central government has a series
of measures to encourage people to buy their own residences. As
part of this, China Construction Bank has 15 billion yuan for
mortgages this year.
</P>
<P>
Hu Angang, a Chinese Academy of Sciences economist, says that
massive spending on infrastructure has been proven to be one of
the most effective ways to stimulate the economy, and, to maintain
annual growth of 8 percent through the year 2000, China needs to
increase infrastructure spending to prevent possible recessions
while creating jobs.
</P>
<P>
State Development Planning Commission officials say that China
is looking for ways to raise money for these capital construction
projects, like raising the cost of public utilities, encouraging
project managers to get funds directly from the capital market, or
attracting more foreign investment and using more low-interest
foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
The central and local governments will also use stocks,
convertible bonds, and industrial funds to finance key capital
projects, the officials say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
