<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Help Save Peace Process in Dual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Prime Minister
Tony Blair said here Sunday that his country will make efforts in
"dual capacity" to help save the long-stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Britain, in the capacity of the government itself as well as
the rotating presidency of the European Union (EU), will do
"whatever we can to find a solution for the peace process," said
Blair at a joint press conference with King Hussein of Jordan
after their meeting at the Royal Palace.
</P>
<P>
Blair admitted that the situation is difficult for the region
as well as for the whole world, but Britain is confident that the
problem can be settled through regional and international efforts.
</P>
<P>
The EU can contribute to a fine turn-out of the process as the
representative of regional countries in Europe, said Blair who
arrived here Sunday on the third leg of his first Middle East tour
since his Labor Party took power in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
"There can be some solutions," but needing goodwill by all the
concerned parties, he added.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the situation between the Arabs and Israel to that in
Northern Ireland, Blair said that there is one common lesson,
which is that "these situations - difficult as they are over many,
many years - can only be resolved if goodwill exists to resolve
them."
</P>
<P>
Blair recently helped broker an agreement between the
Protestants and the Catholics of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"That is why I am here. We will help make progress in the
future," said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians were
stalled over a year ago due to Israel's construction of a Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain will not upstage the United States to play a
leading mediator's role in the Mideast peace process. "We have
remained engaged in the region and act complimentarily to the
U.S. efforts," he added.
</P>
<P>
On his part, King Hussein said "we hope that the current visit
of the prime minister to the area at a very, very critical time
will help us move ahead."
</P>
<P>
Blair later left Jordan for Israel. He has visited Egypt and
Saudi Arabia. Still on his agenda is a visit to the Palestinian
self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
