<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 15:00 GMT, April 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Ahead of the visit to the region by the
U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross, Israeli inner cabinet on
Sunday discussed the second redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Israel Radio, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu convened National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon
and Trade and Industry Minister Natan Sharansky to discuss the
deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
But it was still not clear whether the inner cabinet has
reached a consensus on the extent of the further withdrawal,
which has stalled the peace process for
months. (Israel-Cabinet-Redeployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- A total of 16 people died and at least 12 were
injured in two car crashes in South Africa's southwestern province
of Western Cape Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Eleven people died when two minibuses carrying 23 people
collided near Khayelitsha, about 35 kilometers from Cape Town,
just after 6 a.m., South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
In a separate road accident near Leeu Gamka in Karoo, in the
north of the province, five people were killed and four injured in
the early hours on Sunday. (S. Africa-accidents)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair ended a
two-day visit to Saudi Arabia on Sunday and left for Jordan to
continue his Middle East tour, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Blair left Saudi Arabia with a strong belief on the joint
desire by both countries to push forward the peace march between
Arabs and Israel and his keenness on avoiding further
disappointment for peace," a British diplomat said, quoted by the
news agency.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived in Saudi Red Sea city of Jeddah Saturday on the
second leg of his Mideast tour after wrapping up a visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Britain is holding the rotating presidency of the European
Union (EU). The EU is keen on pushing the peace process
forward. (Saudi-Britain-PM)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said
Sunday that U.S. military aid to Cairo and joint military
exercises with Egypt will continue.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a 150-minute meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Cohen made the pledge at a press briefing with
Egyptian Minister of Defense and Military Production Field Marshal
Hussein Tantawi.
</P>
<P>
"The United States will continue to support Egypt's program to
modernize its military," he told reporters. "This year we are
going to provide Egypt 1.3 billion dollars in grants and our
troops are going to continue exercises and training together."
(Egypt-Cohen-Visit)
</P>
<P>
