<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Leader Meets Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Leader of Israeli opposition
party of Meretz Yossi Sarid met Sunday with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat in the Gaza Strip to discuss ways of breaking the
deadlock in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, also attended by Jordanian Parliament
Deputy Speaker Hamad Tarani, they discussed the idea of forming a
joint delegation to visit the U.S. and Europe, calling for greater
role by the U.S. and the European Union (EU) in reviving the
long-stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Sarid said they would not ask the U.S. and EU to press Israel
because that would produce adverse effects.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that the U.S. and EU would do as they did in
mediating the Northern Ireland peace process. He was referring to
the peace agreement signed early April by the British and Irish
governments and eight political parties in Northern Ireland to end
the deep-running conflict there.
</P>
<P>
Sarid's meeting with Arafat was held a day before a visit by
British Prime Minister Tony Blair here, who had said the Northern
Ireland peace agreement should have an impact on the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Blair, on his first Middle East tour since he took office last
year, is arriving in Israel late Sunday for talks with Israeli
leaders. He said he would inject new impetus into the peace
process with the spirit of conciliation that helped clinch the
Northern Ireland peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister has visited Egypt, Saudi Arabia and
Jordan in his trip which will also take him to the Palestinian
self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
