<HEADLINE> Denmark Takes Second Succssive 5-0 Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion Poul-Erik Hoyer
led Denmark's record-breaking team to its second successive 5-0
victory without dropping a game at the European Championships.
</P>
<P>
The Danes, who followed their 5-0 win over the Netherlands,
defeated the Ukrainians by the same score on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Denmark broke the ground last time two years ago in the home
town of Herning, when it became the first nation to win all six
European gold medals, and is still the favourite to repeat the
achievement.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old Hoyer, who replaced world number two Peter Gade
for the men's singles, was as effective as ever in beating
Ukraine's Michael Mizin by losing only seven points.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, seeded to meet Denmark in Monday's final, beat Scotland
comfortably 4-1, while England suffered a hiccup in beating
Germany 4-1.
</P>
<P>
Darren Hall, the former European men's singles champion, missed
a game point at 14-12 and was beaten 17-14, 15-9 by the German
number one Oliver Pongratz.
</P>
<P>
But from 1-1, England proved too strong in women's singles and
doubles and in men's doubles. 
</P>
