<HEADLINE> Kenyan Sets Women's World Best Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROTTERDAM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Tegla Loroupe ran a solo
race for the world women's best time to win the Rotterdam marathon
in 2 hours, 20 minutes and 47 seconds on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Fabian Roncero failed to become the fastest-ever man
but still won the men's race in 2:07:27.
</P>
<P>
After 10 kilometers, Loroupe already clocked 20 seconds in
short of the women's previous best of 2:21:06 set by Norwegian
Ingrid Kristiansen in London on April 21, 1985.
</P>
<P>
Loroupe, winner of the race last year, coasted home in the
final kilometers with confident strides as the only woman among
the men in the leading field.
</P>
<P>
The men runners, including Portuguese Domingos Castro and
Kenyan Eric Kimayo, ran the first half of the race more than a
minute under the pace of Ethiopian Belayneh Dinsamo's previous
world best of 2:06:50.
</P>
<P>
But Roncero made a sudden break around the 25-kilometer mark
for a spurt of five kilometers before suffering injuries to his
hamstring around the 39-km mark.
</P>
<P>
However, Roncero still managed a final desperate acceleration
to hold off South Korean Bong Ju-Lee who finished second in
2:07.44, ahead of Italy's Danilo Goffi who was third in 2:08.33.
</P>
</TEXT>
