<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwestern China Hit By Strong Winds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A dozen people were reported
missing after strong winds hit the northern and eastern parts of
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in northwest China yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The gale-force winds were accompanied by a duststorm in some
areas as they swept through 10 cities and prefectures, cutting
electricity and water supplies, and causing damage to houses and
destruction of property.
</P>
<P>
By noontime, it had hit northwestern Xinjiang, uprooting or
destroying trees. In the city of Tacheng, rocks picked up by the
wind shattered window glass and caused power and water shortages
for more than ten hours.
</P>
<P>
The regional capital, Urumqi, was hit by more moderate winds
around 11:00 a.m., but they still destroyed large billboards,
trees and power lines, causing blackouts in some
neighborhoods. The yellowish dust that blanketed the city had
still not disappeared at press time.
</P>
<P>
Hami Prefecture in eastern Xinjiang reported 11 people missing
and flocks of sheep and cattle in Altay Prefecture in the north
were scattered.
</P>
<P>
The strong wind also caused forest fires and fires in
residential areas and the regional government and various
departments are involved in emergency operations.
</P>
<P>
According to regional meteorologists, the winds were caused by
a cold air mass from Siberia that hit a warm front from the
Caspian Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
