<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- During the past three months, 452 companies with a
total capital of 1.4 billion Egyptian pounds (411.76 million
U.S. dollars) have been set up in Egypt, the Al-Gomhuria newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
Of the companies, 268 are joint ventures and 184 with limited
liability, according to Chairman of the Egyptian Firm Construction
Bureau Ahmed Fouad Atta.
</P>
<P>
The companies are relating to fields of industry, tourism,
farming production and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran exported 830,000 tonnes of steel in the past
Iranian calendar year ending March 20.
</P>
<P>
This shows an 85 percent increase compared to that in the
previous Iranian year of 1996, Minister of Mines and Metals Eshaq
Jahangiri said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Jahangiri expressed hope that Iran would attain the goal of
producing 12 million tonnes of steel annually within the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman consumed 6.95 billion kilowatt hours (kwh) of
electricity in 1997, a rise of 7.1 percent from 1996, according to
figures released by the Omani Economy Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Oman produced 7.3 billion kwh of electricity last year, 7.3
percent more than 1996.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen's Aden Coastal Fishing Organization is prepared
to export more than 16 tonnes of fish and prawn in a few days, the
Saba News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sultan Ahmed Abdullah, director of the organization's
statistics and planning department said the organization exported
60 tonnes of prawn and fish in both 1997 and 1998, earning more
than 1 million dollars. 
