<HEADLINE> Israeli MPs Oppose Pullout From South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli Knesset
(parliament) members announced here Sunday that they have formed a
movement to oppose suggested unilateral Israeli troop withdrawal
from South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Knesset member Uzi Landau of the ruling Likud group and Labor's
Knesset member Ephraim Sneh said that they have formed a political
movement named "Security for the North," to carry out activities
for this end.
</P>
<P>
The security in the north is vital to Israel and a unilateral
pullout from South Lebanon would damage the country's interests,
they said. It is feared that unilateral Israeli actions would
enable Lebanese guerrillas to launch cross-border attacks, thus
endangering the northern settlements.
</P>
<P>
The two also said that they oppose the activities conducted by
Labor's Knesset member Yossi Beilin and that of the "Four
Mothers," which call on Israel to quit south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"Four Mothers" is a group in Israel formed by four mothers
whose sons were killed in south Lebanon while in service. The name
remains the same even after more people joint the group, which has
been lobbying hard for Israeli troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Landau and Sneh are the first politicians in Israel to openly
oppose unilateral Israeli pullout from South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During the past several months, the pullout issue has become a
hot topic in Israel again as more and more people support the idea
of pulling out the Israel Defense Force from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet decided on April 1 to accept the U.N.
resolution 425, two decades after it was adopted by the Security
Council, and expressed willingness to pull out troops from south
Lebanon provided security arrangements be worked out with Lebanese
government.
</P>
<P>
Both Syria and Lebanon reportedly rejected the Israeli idea of
conditional withdrawal and asked Israel to exit from south Lebanon
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops are operating inside a 1,200-square-kilometer
security zone in south Lebanon set up in 1985 after two invasions
to provide so-called security to northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Military confrontations have been intensified inside the
security zone since the beginning of 1998 between the Israeli
troops and Lebanese resistance groups such as Hezbollah, forcing
Israel to consider an early pullout. 
</P>
</TEXT>
