<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 19 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair ended a two-day visit to Saudi Arabia on Sunday and left for
Jordan to continue his Middle East tour, Kuwait News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"Blair left Saudi Arabia with a strong belief on the joint
desire by both countries to push forward the peace march between
Arabs and Israel and his keenness on avoiding further
disappointment for peace," a British diplomat said, quoted by the
news agency.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived in Saudi Red Sea city of Jeddah Saturday on the
second leg of his Mideast tour after wrapping up a visit to
Egypt. He held talks with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Crown
Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The unidentified British diplomat said that Blair is satisfied
with the talks, during which the he voiced hope that Saudi Arabia
will play a better role in maintaining stability and security in
the Middle East and the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Blair's tour is aimed at helping revive the stalled peace
process and bolstering ties between Britain and the countries he
planned to visit, the diplomat said. Blair will also travel to
Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat said Blair "came to the region with a
responsibility and ideas to activate the peace process," although
he is not carrying any European peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
Britain is holding the rotating presidency of the European
Union (EU). The EU is keen on pushing the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations, the diplomat said that Blair's
talks with the Saudi leaders were "excellent" and covered efforts
to further cement the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Saudi Arabia have signed a number of economic
accords and defense cooperation agreements.
</P>
<P>
Under the defense agreements, Britain will sell 21 billion
U.S. dollars worth of military equipment and weapons to Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Trade exchange between the two countries reached 6.7 billion
dollars in 1997, with about 5 billion dollars in favor of
Britain. 
