<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Researchers Find New Strain Of Hepatitis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese researchers say that a
virus they found in serum samples from hepatitis patients recently
may be a new type of hepatitis virus.
</P>
<P>
The new virus was compared with a virus named TTV that Japanese
scientists discovered last December, and was found to be the same
in 95 percent of the studies, and so is considered to be the
seventh type of hepatitis virus, according to Prof. Wang Haitao,
who led the research at the Chinese Military Academy of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
Five types of viruses were known to cause hepatitis: Hepatitis
A, B, C, D and E, but scientists suspected that there were viruses
that were still unknown because evidence of the five viruses could
not be found in 8 to 15 percent of hepatitis patients, so they
were referred to as Non A-E viruses.
</P>
<P>
The sixth type was discovered by American scientists in 1996,
but was found to cause less than 20 percent of Non A-E hepatitis
cases, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
TTV was found in a hepatitis patient in Japan and was given its
name from the patient's initials. Chinese researchers believed
that TTV could be transmitted through blood transfusions and
possibly other ways, Wang said, so further research is being done
to see how it causes hepatitis and how harmful it is.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine call
the finding very important for treatment and prevention of
hepatitis in China, where 158 out of every 100,000 people become
hepatitis victims and two million new cases are reported each year.
</P>
<P>
"More studies should be made in this field since we're still
unaware of the real causes of eight to twelve percent of hepatitis
cases," says the Academy's Zhan Meiyun. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0072 </DOCNO>
