<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan Province Dredges Rivers to Prevent Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province,
the nation's major rice producer, is intensifying efforts to
dredge rivers and lakes in an attempt to reduce the possibility of
flooding.
</P>
<P>
The province's 5,300 rivers, with a total length of over 90,000
km., present real threats of flooding and make harnessing efforts
extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
However, abundant water resources do not represen the root of
the problem. Instead, experts attribute the vulnerability of
flooding to a number of reasons, including increased silting
resulting from man-made obstructions blocking river channels,
random reclamation and the construction of dams in the upper
reaches of rivers.
</P>
<P>
Surveys show that the depth of riverbeds has decreased by as
much as two meters compared to the early 1950s, with some 150
million tons of silt accumulating on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
Hunan launched a campaign to harness the mainstreams of its
rivers in 1994. The province has since dredged 440 kilometers of
river channels and removed 3,300 obstacles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apartheid Army Used Chimps to Curb Black </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Three British-born
chimpanzees were imported by the former South African Defense
Force (SADF) as the seedbed of a project to reduce the fertility
of black women, The Sunday Independent newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Daniel Goosen, 47, a respected veterinarian and
pathologist, was the first managing director of Roodeplaats
Research Laboratories (RRL), an SADF front company. He headed the
biological program, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"The chimps were a cover for developing an anti-fertility
vaccine," the paper quoted Goosen as saying this week.
</P>
<P>
The only surviving chimp, Daisy, now lives at Johannesburg
zoo.
</P>
<P>
He said the development of an anti-fertility vaccine was the
most important project of the early stages of South Africa's
secret biological warfare programs.
</P>
<P>
"I was told the growing black population, and of course
communism were the overwhelming threats to white South Africa.
The anti-fertility project was approved by the SADF at the
highest levels."
</P>
<P>
"We would have done important research on an inter-species
breeding program, transferring chimpanzee embryos to baboons. If
we had succeeded it would have been a scientific breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
"In transferring the embryo, the recipient baboon may reject
it and in the rejection process the immune system becomes
involved and immunology leads to vaccinology.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine, had we produced it, could have been used
clandestinely on black people."
</P>
<P>
Goosen said he joined the project for patriotic reasons.
</P>
<P>
"I thought we were involved in a war for our survival. We
believed, at the time, this was legitimate. If we developed an
anti-fertility vaccine, we would have curbed the birth rate,
there would be less starving kids. We believed a new government
would also need it."
</P>
<P>
He said he regretted the wrong motivation led to the loss of
opportunities for research.
</P>
<P>
"What we wanted to do then has happened now. There is an
anti-fertility vaccine for cats, for example, and it's useful.
Inter-species embryo transfers are now a fact of life.
</P>
<P>
"We would have been ahead. But we were motivated by the belief
we could decide what was good for others. That was wrong."
</P>
<P>
Goosen has told his colleagues in the scientific world about
his involvement in the secret project that ultimately developed
products to poison anti-apartheid activists, induce heart attacks
and cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
Wouter Basson, head of the project, has been accused of using
the chemical and biological warfare project as a cover for
personal enrichment at an unprecedented cost of the South African
taxpayer. He appeared in court Friday in connection with the
fraud allegations.
</P>
<P>
General Niel Knobel, surgeon-general of the RRL, confirmed
that there was a program investigating fertility but denied it
was aimed at reducing fertility in black women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
