<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Nigerian Parties Adopt Abacha as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Three more Nigerian political
parties Saturday adopted the head of the military government,
General Sani Abacha, as its sole candidate for the August 1
presidential election, following the example of the largest
party, the United Nigeria Congress Party (UNCP).
</P>
<P>
The Congress for National Consensus (CNC) adopted Abacha at
its national convention in Makurdi, Benue State, where a motion
to the effect was moved by its national secretary Mohammed Kola
Balogun and passed by a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party of Nigeria (DPN) and the National Center
Party of Nigeria (NCPN) did the same at their national
conventions in Port Harcourt, Rivers State, and Owerri, Imo
State, Respectively.
</P>
<P>
Both the DPN and CNC amended their constitutions Saturday to
accommodate the candidacy of General Abacha. For example, the DPN
amended the item that restricted candidacy to card-carrying
members only.
</P>
<P>
The UNCP, which saw overwhelming victories in all previous
elections under the military government's transition to civil
rule program, was the first of Nigeria's five registered
political parties to choose Abacha as its flag-bearer.
</P>
<P>
It approved Abacha's candidacy Thursday in Kaduna, at a
special national convention.
</P>
<P>
The fifth party, the Grassroots Democratic Movement (GDM), is
expected to adopt a candidate at its national convention Sunday
in Maiduguri, capital of Borno State.
</P>
<P>
GDM is the only party that has got two aspirants, Mohammed
Yusurf and Tunji Braithweaite.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the suggestion that GDM may also adopt Abacha's
candidacy, former police head Yusurf reportedly said before
leaving Lagos for Maiduguri Saturday that "I do not reckon that
they can be induced or coerced into taking steps damaging to the
nation state as a whole".
</P>
<P>
Though there will be debates at the convention, analysts,
however, believe that the possibility of GDM's choice of Abacha
is high.
</P>
<P>
Should General Abacha become the consensus presidential
candidate of all the five parties, which has been much talked
about hitherto, the next question arising will be whether there
is need for a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
It had been suggested by some quarter of the politicians that
in the above said case, there will be no need for the
presidential election, which will then be replaced by a national
referendum.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled presidential election in August was part of
General Sani Abacha transition to civil rule program announced in
1995, by which he promised to give power to an elected civilian
government in October this year.
</P>
<P>
He has been so far silent on the issue of whether he will run
or not.  
</P>
</TEXT>
