<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Steel Exports Up 85 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran's steel exports increased 85
percent in the past Iranian calendar year (ending March 21, 1998)
over the previous year to reach 830,000 tonnes, the official news
agency IRNA reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Mines and Metals Eshaq Jahangiri said Saturday in
Ahwaz in the southwest province of Khuzestan that the increase
brought the share of steel in non-oil exports to 5.87 percent in
1997 from 3.26 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Iran's steel output was believed to be around 7 million tonnes
in 1997, and the minister said it would achieve an annual target
of 12 million tonnes within three years.
</P>
<P>
Iran's steel industry enjoyed a boom during the past eight
years, with the output rising to 6 million tonnes in 1996. The
government expects a output of 10.5 million tonnes in 1999
following huge investments in the industry.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rapid growth in steel industry, Iran's non-oil
exports dropped by 3.1 percent in 1997 to merely 3 billion
U.S. dollars. This fell far short of the target of 5.5 billion
dollars set for the second five-year development period from 1995
to 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
