<HEADLINE> Cohen Pledges Continuous Military Aid to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said Sunday that U.S. military aid to Cairo and
joint military exercises with Egypt will continue.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a 150-minute meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Cohen made the pledge at a press briefing with
Egyptian Minister of Defense and Military Production Field Marshal
Hussein Tantawi.
</P>
<P>
"The United States will continue to support Egypt's program to
modernize its military," he told reporters. "This year we are
going to provide Egypt 1.3 billion dollars in grants and our
troops are going to continue exercises and training together."
</P>
<P>
That program of U.S.-Egyptian military cooperation will include
15 adventure vehicles with Stinger missiles, two frigates and
torpedos, anti-ship missiles, and co-production of tank-recovery
vehicles, he said.
</P>
<P>
But he did not say if the U.S. might increase military aid to
Egypt to make up for the proposed economic aid cut. He said his
detailed discussion with Tantawi later Sunday will take up this
and other issues.
</P>
<P>
Cairo has been receiving American military and economic aid
since 1979 when it signed peace with Israel. It recently asked the
American administration to reduce the annual 815 million dollar
economic aid it gets from Washington.
</P>
<P>
Washington's allocations in 1998 for Egypt totaled 2.1 billion
U.S. dollars, including some 800 million dollars in economic aid
and nearly 1.3 billion in military aid.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he and Mubarak had a very good meeting and discussed
how to improve bilateral relations and U.S. contributions to the
security of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt and the U.S. have strong strategic partnership in
their shared commitment to stability and peace in the region - "We
both agreed that progress toward a comprehensive Mideast peace
agreement is fundamental to maintaining stability in the region."
</P>
<P>
Cohen reaffirmed the U.S. support to the Mideast peace-making,
saying that U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross will soon return to the
region for talks with the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived here earlier Sunday. His visit coincided with
"Eagle Salute 98'," the annual Egyptian-American joint naval and
airborne drillings that are going on in the Red Sea, American
Embassy Press Attache Rick Roberts told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The two countries conducted military exercises each year since
1979 when Egypt signed a U.S.-brokered peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Cohen has visited Turkey and Jordan and will also travel to
Israel and Greece before he returns home on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
