<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Libya's Secretary (minister) for
Justice Affairs, Mohammed Belqassem Zewai met Saturday night with
a British delegation of representatives of victims of Lockerbie
incident.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan minister discussed proposals put forward by the
British delegation, headed by Dr Jim Swayer, spokesman for
families of the British victims of the Lockerbie incident, on
solving the crisis between Libya and the united states and
Britain, according to a report released by the Jamahiriya News
Agency (JANA) Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Washington and London has been insisting on trying the two
Libyan suspects in bombing a Pan AM passenger plane over the
Scottish town of Lockerbie in 1988, in courts of the States and
Britain. But Libya has been opposing the idea saying that its
nationals would not receive a fair trial in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Jamahiriya News Agency (JANA) said that during the meeting
the two sides discussed some ideas and proposals offered by Jim
Swayer and Professor Robert Black, another leader of the
delegation, on providing a fair trial in a neutral country for the
two Libyan suspects in the bombing which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the families of the British victims of the
Lockerbie incident had arrived in Tripoli on April 16 for talks
with Libyan officials on how to provide a fair trial in a neutral
country for the two Libyan suspects.
</P>
<P>
The British delegation came to Libya from Cairo where it met
and had discussions with the Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel Meguid over the proposals. 
</P>
