<HEADLINE> ASEAN Troika Optimistic About Cambodian Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 19 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN troika, composed of the
foreign ministers of the Philippines, Indonesia and Thailand, said
Sunday that they are optimistic about a "free, fair and credible
election" in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after talks between the three foreign
ministers and representatives from countries of the "friends of
Cambodia," Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said both the
troika and the "friends" welcomed the positive development in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the safe return of former Cambodian First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh to home from March 30 to April 3
and King Norodom Sihanouk's involvement.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at the press conference, the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) troika said that they hoped "a
permanent ceasefire would soon be in force in Cambodia."
</P>
<P>
King Sihanouk made a proposal on March 30 on the ceasefire and
the arrangement by which forces loyal to Prince Ranariddh will
give back the area under their control and reintegrate themselves
into the Royal Cambodian Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
On April 17, Prince Ranariddh issued a statement on
disassociating himself and his forces from the Khmere Rouge and
supporting his father's proposal.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN troika welcomed both the proposal and the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Foreign Minister especially mentioned the displaced
Cambodians sheltered in about 65 refugee camps in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He said his government will soon embark technical discussions
on the refugees' return as part of the efforts to ensure that
every Cambodian could participate in the election, scheduled on
July 26.
</P>
<P>
The troika also discussed the urgent need for international
electoral assistance to Cambodia, including the sending of
observers.
</P>
<P>
"The ASEAN governments have expressed their readiness to send
observers," the troika statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the "friends of Cambodia" also issued a communique,
welcoming the recent positive development in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The "friends" urged the Cambodian government to ensure that all
parties have the opportunity to freely participate.
</P>
<P>
They also called the government to ensure free access to the
media by all parties and to protect human rights of all
Cambodians.
</P>
<P>
The "friends" also welcomed the United Nations' decision to act
as coordinator of the international observation of the elections
in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Right after the press conference, the three foreign ministers
left Bangkok for Siam Reap, Cambodia, for a one-hour talks on the
country's situation with king Sihanouk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
