<HEADLINE> India's Mumbai Port Handles Over 600,000 Containers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Mumbai port remained as India's
largest container port, handling 601,289 containers in the
financial year 1997-98, as against 583,415 in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Sunday from Mumbai that
the overall traffic handled in the docks in 1997-98 registered a
marginal increase from 14.75 million tons in the 1996-97 to 14.86
million tons.
</P>
<P>
The port handled a total traffic of 32.08 million tons,
including petroleum traffic of 16.73 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The port reported a surplus of over 20 billion rupees
(approximately 52 million U.S. dollars) with income at more than
60 billion rupees (over 155 million U.S. dollars) and expenditure
at nearly 40 billion rupees (103 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The port has launched a replacement and modernization program
with total outlay of 98 billion rupees (254 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
