<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Aims to Inject Impetus into Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of his visit to
Israel and the Palestinian lands, British Prime Minister Tony
Blair expressed hope that his visit would inject new impetus into
the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an article carried by the Jerusalem Post Sunday, Blair urged
Israel and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) not to lose
patience or give up efforts in their pursuit of peace despite all
the difficulties facing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Blair is scheduled to arrive here from Saudi Arabia late Sunday
to hold talks with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu before
traveling on to the Gaza Strip Monday for talks with PNA President
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, whose country now holds the rotating
presidency of the European Union (EU), had already met with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on advancing the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
In his article, Blair said "helping to achieve progress is a
key priority for our presidency." "Injecting a new impetus into
the process," he said, "will be central to my visit, and the focus
of my discussions in the region," including with Netanyahu and
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the British and EU policy on the peace
process "is based on our conviction that a lasting resolution
must protect Israel's security and provide a just exchange of
land for peace."
</P>
<P>
Blair hoped the visit would spark new momentum for the peace
process in the spirit of conciliation that culminated in the
recent Northern Ireland peace treaty, which aims to end the
deep-running conflict between Protestants and Catholics.
</P>
<P>
"My experience has taught me that the search for peace is
never easy and that there will be many disappointments along the
way. But we must all keep trying. The present peace process still
offers the best chance for a better future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair said that improving the economic situation in the
Palestinian areas will be a major boost to the peace process. He
said the EU, the leading aid provider to the PNA, promised to
expand the aid package in 1998 under the British presidency.
</P>
<P>
At the practical level, Blair is eager to clinch a long-pending
agreement with the PNA on launching a joint industrial zone at
Karni on the Gaza Strip's east edge and the projected Dahaniya's
airport at its southern end.
</P>
<P>
Noting the leading role played by the United States in
mediating the peace process, Blair said the EU would complement
the U.S. role rather than cut across it.
</P>
<P>
To help rebuild the destroyed trust between Israelis and the
Palestinians, Blair said he would follow up on the plans for an
EU-Palestinian Security Committee discussed during British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook's visit to Gaza last month.
</P>
<P>
Blair's first stop in Israel will be at Yad Vashem, the
Holocaust Memorial, to lay a wreath. He will then talk with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and hold a joint news
conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Blair's itinerary is apparently aimed at soothing Israel's
anger with Cook, who kept Yad Vashem off his agenda and visited
instead a disputed Jewish construction site in east Jerusalem to
show British and EU displeasure with Israel's settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
An infuriated Netanyahu canceled his planned official dinner in
honor of Cook and even refused a handshake before the camera to
register his protest.
</P>
<P>
Israel is the third stop of Blair's Mideast tour, which
includes Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the Palestinian self-rule
areas and Jordan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
