<HEADLINE> 85 Percent of Tap Water Contaminated in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-five percent of the tap
water in Bangladesh's capital of Dhaka has been contaminated, an
English daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The samples, collected recently by the Dhaka Water Supply and
Sewerage Authority (DWSSA) from different city areas, have been
found contaminated with disease-causing coliform micro-organism,
The Daily Star quoted a DWSSA source as saying.
</P>
<P>
"In some areas (in Dhaka), the coliform count was found as high
as 130 per 100 milliliter of water, and the normal reading should
be absolutely zero," he said.
</P>
<P>
Only 15 percent of the samples were found to be containing zero
level coliform count, and coliform count indicates possible
presence of disease-causing micro-organism, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Of the daily water supply of 870 million liter by the DWSSA, 94
percent comes from its 227 deep tubewells while the rest flows
from the existing three surface water treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
Water contamination in distribution lines may be attributed to
leaks in the old pipes, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
