<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Cellphone Giant Invests in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 19 (Xinhua) -- MTN, one of the major
cellular phone companies in South Africa, has launched Uganda's
second licensed telecommunications group with an investment of 30
million U.S. Dollars, local daily Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
This is MTN's second telecom licence in the area. Two weeks
ago it invested 15 million U.S. Dollars for a 26 percent stake in
Rwanda's telecom network.
</P>
<P>
MTN's Ross Macdonald, who drives the group's African
expansion, was quoted as saying that the group was also looking
at opportunities in Zambia, the Democratic Republic of Congo,
Swaziland, Eritrea and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the licence conditions, MTN Uganda will have to
provide 89,000 phone connections over five years.
</P>
<P>
Macdonald said he was confident that the group will be
cash-flow positive after three years and offer an investment
return on share-holders' initial 60 million U.S. Dollars after
seven years.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has one of the lowest teledensities in Africa, with
phone wires reaching only 0.23 percent of the population. In
1970, the country had 100,000 telephone lines, but the turmoil of
the Idi Amin years reduced the figure to a mere 37,000.
</P>
<P>
"We see a potential market of 250,000 subscribers," said
Macdonald, adding that the company would be pushing wireless
technology as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
"In most of Africa, wireless technology makes a lot more
sense, as we have witnessed in rural South Africa, where
previously unserviced areas took to cellphones at a vast rate
when they were introduced," he said.
</P>
<P>
MTN will be relying heavily on its prepaid card system and
will establish its own outlets.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has won global investor appraisal for following
free-market economic policies which have seen average economic
growth rates of six percent this decade. This growth has
attracted other South African investors.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, South African Breweries bought a 40 percent
stake in Uganda's Nile Breweries for 29 million U.S. Dollars,
while Stocks &AMP; Stocks invested an initial six million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola, through its bottler in South Africa, Sabco,
ploughed 35 million Dollars into two bottling facilities in the
country late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
