<HEADLINE> Israel to Present Shopping List of Arms to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Israel is expected to present
United States Defense Secretary William Cohen a list of weapons it
intends to buy for the armed forces during his forthcoming visit,
the Jerusalem Post daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Cohen will pay his first visit to Israel as defense minister on
Monday and hold talks on military cooperation with Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
The talks will focus on Israel's long-term modernization plans
of the armed forces and high on the agenda will be Israel's demand
that the U.S. fund its acquisition of a third Arrow anti-ballistic
missile battery, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen promised in principle to meet the Israeli demand during
Mordechai's visit to Washington last month. Israel will be trying
to translate the U.S. commitment into action, according to the
daily.
</P>
<P>
The Arrow missile system is a joint project of Israel and the
U.S.. It has yet to be put into operation.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai is also expected to push for U.S. commitment to
widen bilateral strategic cooperation, including a continued U.S.
commitment to maintaining Israel's qualitative edge in weaponry,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the weaponry Israel has sought from the United States
is for the air force. The U.S. has recently approved the sale to
Israel of a Longbow upgrade for its fleet of Apache helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is currently on a regional tour, which has taken him to
Turkey, Jordan and Egypt. He will leave Israel for Greece on
Tuesday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
