<HEADLINE> German Opposition Leader to Visit Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Vice president of the Social
Democratic Party (SDP) in the German parliament Gunger Verhugen is
to pay a two-day visit to Tehran Monday to repair bilateral
relations between Iran and Germany, the pro-government daily
newspaper Iran news reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Verhugen's visit is the first trip by the highest German
socialist official to Iran since the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
It is considered as important particularly after the political
row between the two countries triggered by a Berlin court rule
which accused Iranian leaders of supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the high chances of winning the upcoming October
elections by the Socialists in Germany, the daily noted,
Verhugen's visit will be of great significance from the political
point of view and will have important impact on Tehran-Bonn
relations.
</P>
<P>
Iran News said that Verhugen would meet with Iranian parliament
members and other officials to discuss bilateral ties and the case
of the German citizen Helmut Hoffer who was sentenced to death in
Iran for having illegal sexual relations with an Iranian woman.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries cooled down since April
last year after the Berlin local court ruled that Iranian leaders
were behind the assassination of four Iranian Kurdish rebel
leaders in the Mykonos restaurant in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
The rule provoked members of the European Union (EU) to
withdraw their ambassadors from Tehran, who returned last November
after the EU reached a deal with Iran over the Mykonos case.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the detente between the EU and Iran, the Bonn-Tehran
rapprochement was retarded by Hoffer's case and German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel warned that Bonn-Tehran ties would be
damaged if Iran carried out the death sentence on Hoffer.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Verhugen would try to convince the Iranian
government to release Hoffer, a German merchant, who was arrested
last September with his Iranian fiancee on charges of having
sexual relations with a Muslim woman. The Iranian laws ban
relations between a non-Muslim man and a Muslim woman.
</P>
<P>
However, Hoffer claimed that he has converted to Islam before
having a case with the Iranian woman. Reports said that the
Iranian judiciary was reconsidering his case according to his
latest claim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
