<HEADLINE> Jerusalem Mayor to Boycott State Dinner for Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert
will not attend the state dinner for British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, who will arrive here Sunday afternoon, The Jerusalem Post
reported.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that Olmert conveyed this message to Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Saturday night, saying that he
took this action because Blair said he would not meet with Olmert
during his visit in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Olmert charged that this was " a deviation from protocol and
in sharp contrast with the pattern set by his predecessor, John
Major."
</P>
<P>
"The Foreign Ministry's efforts ended in failure and I am
astounded at this outcome, " Olmert said. The mayor accused the
government of "giving in."
</P>
<P>
But political sources said that the British leader's staff
indicated that a meeting with Olmert would necessitate a
concomitant session with the representative in Jerusalem of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), Faisal Husseini.
</P>
<P>
This evidently promoted British and Israeli officials to
conclude that it would be best to leave the Jerusalem
municipality off the itinerary.
</P>
<P>
The status of Jerusalem is a sensitive issue in
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, which is due to be solved in
the final settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed that Jerusalem is its indivisible capital,
while Palestinians wanted to establish an independent state with
the East Jerusalem as its future capital.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook was snubbed last
month during his visit in Israel, due to his meeting with a
Palestinian Legislative Council member at a controversial Jewish
settlement in the East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Blair, also representing the European Union, began a five-day
trip to the Middle East on Friday. He will hold talks with
Netanyahu on Sunday and meet PNA President Yasser Arafat in
Gaza City Monday. 
</P>
