<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, Russia Agree to Sign a Broader Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto have agreed to work
toward signing a wider treaty that will cover not only peace but
also friendship and cooperation into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
This came Sunday as a result of a two-day official summit
between the two leaders in Kawana, about 130 kilometers southwest
of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin proposed the idea of making the new treaty broader than
a peace treaty in his first round of talks with Hashimoto Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference Sunday, he said he had not changed
his stance since the 1993 Tokyo Declaration under which the two
countries agreed to conclude a peace treaty after solving the
territorial dispute based on the principle of "law and justice."
</P>
<P>
The status of the four Russian-held islands off Japan's
northernmost main island of Hokkaido has long prevented the two
countries from concluding a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin vowed to speed up efforts toward a peace treaty on the
Russian side.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said he agreed with Yeltsin to soon hold a new round
of bilateral talks between vice foreign ministers on the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Turning to bilateral economic cooperation, Hashimoto said they
agreed that the two countries will jointly set up a company to
promote Japanese investment in Russia.
</P>
<P>
A team of officials from Japan's Foreign Ministry, Finance
Ministry and Ministry of International Trade and Industry
will visit Russia early May to discuss the issue, Hashimoto said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin arrived in Japan Saturday for his second informal
summit with Hashimoto following their previous unofficial talks
last November in Krasnoyarsk, eastern Siberia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
