<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Arrives for Talks With Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen arrived here Sunday morning for talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on the third stop of his Mideast tour.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who flew in from Amman for a two-day official visit, is
expected to meet later with Egyptian Minister of Defense and
Military Production Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi to discuss
cooperation in the field of defense.
</P>
<P>
His talks with Mubarak Sunday morning are expected to focus on
bilateral relations, the Mideast peace process and other issues of
mutual interests.
</P>
<P>
Cohen has visited Turkey and Jordan and will also travel to
Israel and Greece before he returns home on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on
the eve of Cohen's visit here, American Ambassador to Egypt Dan
Kurtzer expressed his country's belief that its new peace
initiative is a "balanced proposal" that the Palestinians and
Israelis can work through.
</P>
<P>
Yet he declined to say whether the initiative would achieve the
wanted progress or not. Washington will send its Mideast Peace
Envoy Dennis Ross by the end of this week in a new bid to reach a
conciliatory approach by Palestinians and Israelis on the
U.S. proposals, he told reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Cairo has been receiving American military and economic aid
since 1979. But it has offered recently to the Clinton
administration to reduce the annual 815 million dollar economic
aid it gets from Washington.
</P>
<P>
Washington's allocations in 1998 for Egypt totaled 2.1 billion
U.S. dollars, including 800 million dollars in economic aid and 1.3
billion in military aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
