<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, April 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto have agreed to work toward signing a
wider treaty that will cover not only peace but also friendship
and cooperation into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
This came Sunday as a result of a two-day official summit
between the two leaders in Kawana, about 130 kilometers southwest
of Tokyo. (Japan-Russia-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- A top leader of the Russian Communist Party said
Saturday that he believed his party would suggest voting for
President Boris Yeltsin's choice for premier at the party's April
23 plenum.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Seleznev, speaker of the State Duma (the lower house),
said in a televised interview that he would urge his follow
communists to support Sergei Kiriyenko as premier in the hope of
saving the Duma. (Russia-Communist)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- A fire gutted 32 houses in East Jakarta Saturday,
leaving at least 128 people homeless, an official said.
</P>
<P>
No one was injured in the incident and losses were still being
calculated Saturday night, Head of the East Jakarta Fire
Department Yoyon Ardisoma said.
</P>
<P>
He said that an electrical short circuit was believed to have
caused the blaze. (Indonesia-Fire)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Macedonian Foreign Minister Blagoj Hanziaki opposed
economic sanctions against Belgrade despite U.S. Deputy Secretary
of State Strobe Talbott's promise that the sanctions would not
harm neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Winding up a brief visit to Macedonian capital Skopje on
Saturday, Talbott told a press conference there that any sanction
directed against Belgrade for its failure to meet international
demands should not harm its neighboring countries. (Macedonia-US)
</P>
</TEXT>
