<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Headman Calls for Intensified Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A Zambian traditional leader has
urged the government to intensify the crop diversification
instead of distributing relief food, which he said makes people
lazy.
</P>
<P>
Headman Benson Shikubomba in Southern Province criticized in
Choma Saturday the food relief program, charging that the program
is making villagers lazy, the Zambia Daily Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Sunday quoted him as saying that the
government should give out agriculture inputs like fertilizer to
farmers other than distributing relief food because the trend is
killing hard work among villagers.
</P>
<P>
The government should ensure that only the needy benefits from
the program and not every villager, he said.
</P>
<P>
The headman made the appeal at a seeds distribution and
multiplication field day in Choma.
</P>
<P>
Southern Province agricultural coordinator Darius Hakayobe
urged the farmers to work hard to achieve household food
security.
</P>
<P>
Hakayobe said crop diversification is the only means to
achieving food security and avert hunger at household levels.
</P>
<P>
Sweden has granted 12 million Swedish Kroner (about 1.6
million US Dollars) to the multiplication and distribution of
improved seed project.
</P>
<P>
Project coordinator Harry Ngoma said the projects operating in
northern, northwestern, western and southern provinces have
already trained small-scale farmers as seed growers who will this
season produce seeds for their communities on sale.
</P>
<P>
Ngoma said the project is meant to develop a seed bank within
the locality of the farmers who can not be accessed by the
commercial sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
