<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Holds Talks with Saudi Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Agency quoted a British diplomatic source as saying that
the talks centered on the stalled Mideast peace process including
Israel's offer to pull out from south Lebanon, developments in the
Gulf region and Gulf-Iran ties improvement.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan-western standoff over the 1988 Pan-AM flight bombing
over Lockerbie, Scotland was also top on the agenda, he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived in Jeddah from Cairo earlier Saturday on the
second leg of his Middle East tour, including stops in Egypt, Saudi
Arabia, Jordan, Israel and the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
He said his objectives of the current tour was trying to
reactivate the peace process and to boost British ties with
countries he planned to visit. But he denied caming to launch a
European initiative on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said Europe could only play a complementary and supporting
role in the process and was not likely to do anything to upstage
washington as the region's chief peace mediator.
</P>
<P>
While refusing to condemn Israel's obstinate policy on the
peace-making, Blair urged the Israel's right-wing leaders
to honor signed agreements on troops withdrawal from the occupied
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Blair and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak agreed Friday that
additional efforts should be employed to build confidence among
parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
He also reportedly warned leaders of Mideast countries that the
 dangerous deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace process was
threatening the stability of the entire region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
