<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maintains Tight Debt Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to exercise
tight control over the scale and structure of external borrowing,
according to an official from the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange (SAFE).
</P>
<P>
The official from the foreign capital and debt management
department of the administration was quoted as saying by today's
Business Weekly of China Daily that SAFE's supervision over
financial institutions will be tightened and measures will be
taken to stem disguised foreign borrowing.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that SAFE encourages borrowers to take steps
to disperse risks relating to changes in exchange rates and
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In principle, the official said, foreign debt can only be used
to finance infrastructure, the high and new technology sectors and
equipment refurbishment by State enterprises, and to boost
companies' export capacity.
</P>
<P>
Foreign borrowing for use in real estate is restricted, and may
not be used to fund duplicate projects.
</P>
<P>
A number of State firms will be allowed to raise foreign funds
directly in overseas capital markets, with the aim of easing the
burden of foreign debt repayments on financial institutions and
expanding capital sources for enterprises.
</P>
<P>
SAFE has already given approval to several large State firms,
such as Baoshan Iron and Steel Corp, the China National
Aero-technology Import and Export Corp, China Technology Import
and Export Corp and China National Offshore Oil Corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
