<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Backs Cambodia to Hold Elections In July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan has voiced support for Cambodia to hold elections
according to the original schedule.
</P>
<P>
Surin told reporters Saturday night that rival factions in
Cambodia should reach a permanent ceasefire before then.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking after a working dinner of ASEAN's troika of
Indonesia, the Philippines and Thailand appointed last year to
mediate in the Cambodian conflict.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian politician Sam Rainsy earlier required the elections
to be postponed till late this year, citing the unpreparedness in
legal institutions and instruments necessary for a free and fair
political contest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Surin, in apparent reference to Rainsy's remark, said all sides
consulted by the troika "leaned toward" the idea of holding the
elections on July 26 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
They also felt that the question of pardon for military
commanders loyal to ousted co-premier Norodom Ranariddh should not
become a "condition" that would obstruct this event, he added.
</P>
<P>
But the Thai minister stressed the final decision on the matter
rested with Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) appointed
the troika to help facilitate political stability in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The troika members were currently meeting here to enhance
consultations following the death of Pol Pot, former leader of the
Khmer Rouge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
