<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign-Invested Firms to Enjoy Better Arbitration Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Foreign-invested companies in
China will soon be able to receive arbitration service from the
China International Economic and Trade Arbitration Commission
(CIETAC), today's Business Weekly of China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The Weekly said that the revised CIETAC Arbitration Rules,
which expand CIETAC's arbitration scope to include disputes
between foreign-funded firms and legal and natural entities in
China, are expected to go into effect soon after the draft is
ratified by relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
CIETAC at present accepts foreign-related disputes but seldom
handles disputes involving foreign-invested firms and other
Chinese entities since foreign-funded firms are registered and
operate in China and therefore are considered legal entities of
China.
</P>
<P>
Under the revised rules, the period for the respondent to
submit his written defence and for CIETAC to make awards will be
shorter than those for foreign-related disputes. At present,
arbitration awards are made within nine months of the formation of
the panel of arbitrators.
</P>
<P>
The fees charged for arbitration of disputes between
foreign-invested firms and other legal or natural entities of
China will also be lower than those charged for arbitration of
foreign-related disputes, and will be decided in accordance with
relevant regulations relating to fees charged for arbitration of
domestic disputes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
