<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Privatize T &AMP; T Board in Two Phases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
privatize its Bangladesh Telegraph and Telephone Board (BTTB) in
two phases under a plan, the Associated Press of Bangladesh (APB)
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The phase one of the restructuring plan will be a
corporatisation process of the state-owned BTTB, according to the
National Telecommunications Policy 1998, approved by the cabinet
late last month and expected to be placed in parliament shortly
for endorsement.
</P>
<P>
During the process, the BTTB will be made a limited entity,
called Bangladesh Telecommunications Company Ltd., instead of
being a government department.
</P>
<P>
At this stage, the government will continue to own 51-100
percent of its shares. However, the new company will have full
responsibility of managing assets and operations, and will also be
fully accountable for its own profitability.
</P>
<P>
In the second phase, the BTTB will be fully privatized, with
the government selling out all its shares to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of engaging an internationally-reputed foreign
telephone firm as a strategic and managing partner of the BTTB
will also be explored, the policy anticipates.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has not set any timeframe for
completing the whole process, the reported noted, adding that the
policy had recommended opening up of all telecom services
including basic lines for the private sector by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
In order to make the BTTB function effectively and commercially
in competition with other private operators in a liberalized
environment, the requisite administrative and adequate financial
and commercial authority will be delegated to it.
</P>
<P>
The non-core function within the BTTB will be gradually
divested and could be contracted out to qualified private parties.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the corporate restructuring period, the BTTB, with
the government's approval, will be authorized to raise necessary
capital for the expansion of its existing and introduction of new
services.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government will also consider privatizing
two state-owned telecom equipment manufacturers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
