<HEADLINE> Peace Process in Tajikistan "Irreversible": Polish FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The peace process in Tajikistan
has just begun and is still fragile at present, but it is
"irreversible," said Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek in
Dushambe, capital of Tajikistan, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Geremek, also the current president of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), said the OSCE realized
that a sustained peace and stability in Tajikistan was important
for Central Asia and the entire region of the OSCE.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference following his one-day visit,
Geremek said that it is an important stage to implement the
agreements on incorporating rebel forces into government power
agencies, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
He added "the peace precess was delayed for some time," but he
hoped the task could be finished by the middle of this year, so as
to create favorable conditions for parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
Geremek said both Tajik President Emomali Sharipovich Rakhmonov
and he believed that the OSCE should do more within its power to
help the country achieve peace.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE is willing to help it reform its constitution,
election laws and carry out parliamentary elections, he added.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Geremek held talks with Rakhmonov, Primer
Minister Yakhya Azimov, Foreign Minister Talbak Nazarov and United
Tajik Opposition leader A. Nuri.
</P>
<P>
The Polish foreign minister left Dushambe for Uzbekistan on
Saturday. Before his came here, he had visited Turkmenistan,
Kazakhstan and Kyrghyztan. The five countries joined the OSCE two
years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
