<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Jobless Rate to Rise Sharply: ILO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) predicted that unemployment outlook in Thailand
is dimmer than the government estimation this year due to negative
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The number of layoffs would surpass the official projection of
under two million and the unemployment rate would reach 5.6
percent by the end of this year, the ILO said in its latest report
received here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the rise to the government's revision of
the economic growth target from zero to minus 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The entry of 500,000 new Thai job seekers this year would
worsen the unemployment situation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Two thirds of the job seekers, it said, comprise people who
have completed their lower secondary schools and beyond.
</P>
<P>
"This group is probably most at risk of failing to find work
and of adding to the number of recorded unemployed," the report
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the problem are Thai construction workers in
Malaysia, Singapore and South Korea whose jobs have become
uncertain as a result of the slowdown in the sector, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Out of 60,000 Thais working in Singapore, 85 percent are
construction workers, and out of the 110,000 in Malaysia, 20,000
are at construction sites, according to the ILO.
</P>
<P>
The report, which concentrates on situations in Thailand,
Indonesia and South Korea, would serve as a guideline for a
three-day international meeting between government officials,
employers and workers beginning in Bangkok next Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
