<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Investment May Drop 44 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government had
only approved foreign investment projects worth 5.3 billion U.S.
dollars up till last week, and the total foreign investments in
1998 may decline by more than 44 percent compared with those of
last year, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"If this trend become a reality, the foreign investments which
will enter Indonesia up till the end of this year may total less
than 20 billion dollars, while the normal figure in the last five
years was averaged at 30 billion dollars," Investment Minister
Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo said here Saturday, Antara News Agency
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the government approved foreign investments totaling
29.9 billion dollars, and in 1997, despite the monetary crisis
since mid-July, approved foreign investments still amounted to
33.8 billion dollars, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months of this year, he said, the flow of
foreign investment into the country was still steady, but then
sharply declined in the third and fourth months.
</P>
<P>
Most foreigners invested in gas and electricity, housing and
industrial estates, agriculture, chemical and metal industries,
added the minister. 
</P>
