looks certain to be re-elected in Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
Latest polls predict Klestil will win outright with 54 percent
to 60 percent. Nearly 6 million people will cast their ballots
and Klestil needs more than 50 percent of the votes cast to avoid
a May runoff.
</P>
<P>
Klestil, 65, was a career diplomat until he succeeded Kurt
Waldheim as president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
His four challengers are Gertraud Knoll, 39, a female
Protestant bishop, Heide Schmidt, 49, chairwoman of the small
Liberal Forum, Construction tycoon Richard Lugner, 65, and Karl
Walter Nowak, a publicist and environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian presidency is largely ceremonial. General
elections over who will be the next chancellor, Austria's
equivalent of prime minister, is still a year away.
</P>
<P>
Austria is currently ruled by a coalition of the leading
Socialists and the conservative People's Party. 
