which is the biggest commercial bloc in South America grouping
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, with Chile and Bolivia as
its associate members:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Southern Common Market and the Andean
Community of Nations signed on April 16 in Buenos Aires a
framework agreement to create a free trade area starting 2000.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulates that by the start of that year all
custom tariff barriers and other restrictions that affect trade
will have been eliminated in south America, through a gradual
process.
</P>
<P>
The document fixes September 30 as the deadline for
negotiations of an agreement of custom tariff preferences.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur and CAN have a population of some 297 million people
and add up to a gross domestic product of more than 1 billion
U.S. dollars, equivalent to 13 percent of the total of the
American countries committed to create the Free Trade Area of the
Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Presidents Hugo Banzer of Bolivia and Fernando
Henrique Cardoso of Brazil signed a statement on April 17
emphasizing the need to strengthen the political and economic
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Banzer and Cardoso underscored the importance of the project of
the 3,125 kilometer long gas pipeline between Santa Cruz de la
Sierra (Bolivia) and Sao Paulo and Porto Alegre (Brazil).
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina produced 48.4 million cubic meters of
crude oil last year, 6.3 percent more than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Gas production amounted to 37.076 billion cubic meters, 7
percent more than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas exports were 19.339 million cubic meters and 1.142
million cubic meters respectively, with increases of 2.4 percent
and 59 percent compared with those in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, Chile and the United States are the main importers of
Argentine oil.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil received 40.2 billion dollars from abroad
during the first quarter of this year, twice the figure obtained
in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Brazil said that in March the country
received 20.7 billion dollars, of which 12.8 billion were foreign
loans.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, capital inflow into the country during the first
half of April amounted to 1.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's international reserves reached 67.8 billion dollars in
March.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile and Mexico signed a free trade agreement on
April 17, on the eve of the start of the Second Summit of the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Chilean President Eduardo Frei and
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, substitutes and expands the
Economic Complementation Accord signed by the two countries in
1991.
</P>
<P>
The two nations agreed to eliminate all the subsidies to the
export of agricultural and livestock products by January 1 of
2003, and for non-agricultural products they will follow the
guidelines of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Chile-Mexico trade underwent a significant increase, going from
158 million dollars in 1990 to 1.452 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile and the United States signed a trade
cooperation agreement on April 17 to expand the flow of
investments.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Chilean Economy Minister Alvaro
Garcia and United States Secretary of Commerce William Daley
during the visit of President Bill Clinton to Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
