<HEADLINE> Myanmar Farmers Urged to Use Irrigation Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Tin Oo urged the
country's farmers to systematically use irrigation water for
successful cultivation of the four pillar crops -- paddy, beans
and pulses, cotton and sugarcane.
</P>
<P>
Tin Oo, second secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and
Development Council (SPDC), made the remarks at inauguration
ceremony for a reservoir -- Saddan -- in Magway division Saturday,
attended by Than Shwe, SPDC chairman, The New Light of Myanmar
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tin Oo said the reservoir, which can irrigate over 4,050
hectares, would help develop the arid region and boost
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the greening projects are being extended to
13 districts from nine in arid regions in central Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
He urged the farmers to use irrigation water systematically.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, a total of 86 reservoirs and
dams have been built in Myanmar since 1988, irrigating 535,400
hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the mainstay of Myanmar's economy and paddy is
one of the country's four pillar crops. Its rice export, which
maintained an average annual figure of 463,750 tons in the last
four-year plan period (1992-93 to 1995-96), fetched 88 million
U.S. dollars annually, 40 percent of the country's foreign
exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
The country's paddy production in the 1996-97 season was 17.08
million tons with 93,000 tons of rice exported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
