<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Funding Gap Requires Rapid Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A concrete fund-raising scheme
for China's massive infrastructure program is urgently needed to
give the economy real impetus, according to today's Business
Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The importance has been underlined by China's sluggish economic
indices for the first three months of 1998, which reflect weak
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials said early this year China would rely heavily
on new infrastructure projects to stimulate domestic demand in
pursuit of economic growth of eight percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Industrial enterprises are waiting impatiently for the
infrastructure building spree, which will help them cut stockpiles
and create opportunities for new production, the Weekly said.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistics Bureau reports that the retail price index
fell 1.5 percent on a year-on-year basis during the January-March
period, compared to a rise of 2.6 percent in the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Falling prices, rising promotional spending and unchanged
management costs have greatly squeezed industrial firms' profits,
which slumped more than 83 percent compared to the first quarter
of last year, an official source said. Added-value output of the
industrial sector grew 8.2 percent during the January-March
period, representing a fall of 2.8 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Economists say it is a common scenario in China for economic
growth to proceed slowly in the first three months but accelerate
in the remaining three quarters. Moreover, new economic policies
always need five or six months before their effects are felt.
</P>
<P>
However, without a clear financing scheme for the core part of
the new economic kick-start program, worries persist.
</P>
<P>
Fixed-asset investment in the central government budget fell in
1998, meaning funding for the infrastructure projects must come
from elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
