<HEADLINE> Brazilian Soybean Exports Diminish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Brazil, second biggest
producer and exporter of soybeans in the world, registered a 2.3
percent reduction in its exports of the product in the first
quarter of this year against the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country exported 751,700 tons of soybeans in the first
quarter of this year against the 769,400 tons sold abroad in the
same period of 1997, according to data released Saturday by the
Brazilian Organization of Statistics of Soy Grain, Meal and Oil.
</P>
<P>
The export of soybean meal in the same period reached 1.145
million tons, a drop of 10.8 percent from the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country exported more than 103,000 tons of soybean oil in
the first quarter of this year, against the 145,200 tons in the
same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the export of soybeans and byproducts is attributed
by Brazilian observers to the reduction of the price in the
international market. Brazil had last year a total income of more
than 5.5 billion U.S. dollars from the export of soybeans and
byproducts. 
</P>
