<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Crudes Basket Price Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The price of the Venezuelan
basket of crudes and byproducts for export rose one U.S. dollar
between Wednesday and Friday this week, going up from 11.70
dollars to 12.70 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
According to data released Saturday by the Energy and Mines
Ministry, the figure on Friday meant a gain of 1.37 dollars from a
week ago, when the price was 11.33 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) basket
of crudes closed last Friday at 13.49 dollars per barrel, a gain
of 1.21 dollars over the past week.
</P>
<P>
The quotations of the different crudes sold in the
international market strengthened over the past days because of
the possibility that Iraq will export only 3 billion U.S. dollars
worth of oil, instead of 5.2 billion dollars, under the Oil for
Food program brokered by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
This changed the outlook for the participants in the market,
because the Iraqi crude supply will not surpass 1.6 million
barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Mexico and Venezuela initiated between
independent oil producers and OPEC an agreement on the reduction
of oil supply in Riyadh March 21. 
</P>
