<HEADLINE> Macedonia Opposes Sanctions Against Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian Foreign Minister Blagoj
Hanziaki opposed economic sanctions against Belgrade despite
U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott's promise that the
sanctions would not harm neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Winding up a brief visit to Macedonian capital Skopje on
Saturday, Talbott told a press conference there that any sanction
directed against Belgrade for its failure to meet international
demands should not harm its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The United States and other members of the six-nation
International Contact Group for Former Yugoslavia would work for
this goal, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Macedonian foreign minister insisted that
sanctions against Belgrade were "unacceptable to Macedonia and
other neighboring countries."
</P>
<P>
Such measures would severely harm Macedonia's reforms and its
efforts to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and
the European integrity, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the Kosovo crisis, Macedonia had
repeatedly voiced opposition to sanctions against Belgrade, noting
it would bring about harmful consequences.
</P>
<P>
The 1992-1995 Western sanctions against Belgrade had caused
great economic losses to Macedonia, Bulgaria and other neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
Talbott also had talks with Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov
and Prime Minister Branko Cvenkovski during his several hours of
stay in Skopje. 
</P>
</TEXT>
