<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Oil Price Falls Force Cuts in Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 19 (Xinhua) -- China's petroleum sector is
suffering serious oversupply and financial losses as a result of
falls of crude oil prices on the international market, today's
Business Weekly of China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Weekly, China National Petroleum Corporation
(CNPC), the largest oil producer in the country, has already told
its oilfields to cut output, reduce investment and enlarge sales
to reach a balance of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
China Petrochemical Corporation (Sinopec) has also decided to
process less crude oil and manufacture fewer oil products to
reduce losses, it said.
</P>
<P>
The average price for crude oil on the international market has
plunged from 22 US dollars per barrel last September to 13 US
dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The average domestic crude oil price in China is around 15 US
dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Cheaper crude oil and oil products from abroad therefore pose a
major threat to domestic oil producers and refineries.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the Weekly pointed out, the Chinese Government
approved the importation of 1.8 million tons of oil products --
mainly diesel -- in the first quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, rampant smuggling is bringing in more cheap oil
products from abroad.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a vast glut of diesel fuel has forced domestic
refineries to reduce or even halt production. Consequently, they
have been ordering less crude from the oilfields.
</P>
<P>
China's major oilfields have had to close wells because their
storage tanks were full. In the first quarter, the country's eight
leading oilfields shut 2,607 wells.
</P>
<P>
CNPC's oilfields reduced crude oil output by 590,000 tons in
the first three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980419.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland to Shut Down Nearly Half Coal Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Polish government has worked
out a plan to shut down nearly half of the nation's coal mines in
a restructuring effort to revive the ailing coal industry.
</P>
<P>
The government will shut down 12 loss-making mines this year
and close another 24 major loss-makers in the next three years,
reducing the number of coal mines from the current 65 to 32 or 36
by the year 2002, the Gazeta Wyborcza newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 24 major loss-makers suffered a loss of nearly 300 million
U.S. dollars last year, accounting for 60 percent of the year's
total loss of the debt-ridden industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the restructuring program, the government will lay off
120,000 workers, sell some mines to private businesses and relax
its control on coal prices. The government also plans to pump some
20 billion dollars of new investment into the industry to make it
profitable by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
