<HEADLINE> Berlusconi Elected Head of Forza Italia Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Silvio Berlusconi, Italy's media
tycoon and one-time prime minister, on Saturday formalized his
position as the head of the conservative Forza Italia party he
founded four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Berlusconi was elected party president overwhelmingly by some
3,000 delegates attending a three-day national congress held in
Milan. He was the only candidate for the party presidency.
</P>
<P>
A rally by about 50,000 supporters through the streets of
downtown Milan capped the congress, the first ever by the party
since it was formed in 1993 after corruption scandals swept away
long-ruling Christian Democrats and Socialists.
</P>
<P>
Once hailed as a breath of fresh air to Italy's decades of
political sleaze until he was charged with corruption himself,
Berlusconi wanted to make Forza Italia the main opposition to the
center-left government of Premier Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
He told his supporters that their party might sweep 33 percent
of votes in the next elections.
</P>
<P>
Berlusconi led the Freedom Alliance to victory in 1994
parliamentary elections. But squabbling within his coalition
ended his premiership later that year and has ever since
challenged his leadership of the alliance, which includes his own
party, the right-wing National Alliance, and tiny groupings of
ex-Christian Democrats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
