<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel on Saturday
dismissed rising doubt about a quick compromise on the dispute
over who will head the future European central bank, saying the
European Union states are set to make a choice at their summit in
Brussels in early May.
</P>
<P>
The top post of the European central bank, which will set
monetary policy for all EU states adopting the planned single
European currency, are now contested by the former Dutch central
bank leader and the current head of the European Monetary
Institute, Wim Duisenberg, as well as the French central chief,
Jean-Claude Trichet. (Germany-EU-Bank Chief)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Visiting Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto held their first round of
informal talks Saturday to discuss ways to promote bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
At the first of two "no-necktie" talks at Japan's seaside
resort of Kawana, about 130 kilometers southwest of Tokyo, the two
leaders agreed on reciprocal visits by Hashimoto to Moscow this
fall and by Yeltsin to Tokyo next year.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who arrived earlier in the day at Tokyo's Haneda
airport and immediately flew by helicopter to Kawana, was quoted
as telling Hashimoto that he wants to promote ties on both the
economic and political fronts through a series of vigorous
political exchanges. (Japan-Russia-Talks)
