<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Presents 10-Point Program to Assist Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) presented a 10-point action plan to the 35 leaders
gathered here Saturday, reaffirming its commitment to accelerated
economic and social progress in Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the Second Summit of the Americas, IDB
President Enrique V. Iglesias outlined the Bank's contributions to
help the region achieve sustainable development upon the approach
of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The 10 points of the program include:
</P>
<P>
Provide 40 billion U.S. dollars in financing, an average of 8
billion dollars annually for the five-year period beginning this
year, and another 3 billion dollars in concessional loans during
the same period;
</P>
<P>
Dedicate half the resources, a total of 20 billion dollars, to
social sectors, for investments in health, education, sanitation,
defense of vulnerable groups, neighbourhood improvement, support
for microenterprise, and the strengthening of the networks of
social assistance to reduce poverty and improve social equity;
</P>
<P>
Double the amount of loans for education to a minimum of 5
billion dollars by the year 2002, as well as promote regional
activities and include interships, virtual schools, distance
education and information for education;
</P>
<P>
Mobilize some 20 billion dollars in the next 5 years in private
sector investment, through direct participation in the projects,
for infrastructure, such as roads, energy health, water
irrigation;
</P>
<P>
Lend a minimum of 500 million dollars in the next four years to
microenterprise, and carry out special programs to support small
and medium-sized enterprises. Both groups together constitute 99
percent of the enterprises in the region, a total of 50 million
entities;
</P>
<P>
Continue support for the development of modern financial system
and reinforce capacity of banking supervision, working with both
public and private sectors;
</P>
<P>
Contribute to the integration process through the creation of a
"regional facility for commerce," with initial resources of 50
million dollars annually, to help countries strengthen the
capacity of technical negotiating teams and respond to the demands
of the new international commercial agenda;
</P>
<P>
Continue strengthening judicial systems as the essential
pillars for an efficient market economy and of just and
participatory democratic systems;
</P>
<P>
Create the appropriate financing mechanisms for a more dynamic
civil society and provide support for dialogue and cooperation
among governments, civil society and the private sector;
</P>
<P>
Support the region efforts to use informatics technology in
areas such as social security, health, education, tax and customs
administration, land titling, and administration of justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
