<HEADLINE> Germany Insists on Quick Decision on EU Bank Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
on Satursday dismissed rising doubt about a quick compromise on
the dispute over who will head the future European central bank,
saying the European Union states are set to make a choice at their
summit in Brussels early May.
</P>
<P>
The top post of the European central bank, which will set
monetary policy for all EU states adopting the planned single
European currency, are now contested by the former Dutch central
bank leader and the current head of the European Monetary
Institute, Wim Duisenberg, as well as the French central chief,
Jean-Claude Trichet.
</P>
<P>
Although most other EU states favor the Dutchman, France has so
far firmly insisted on its own nomination.
</P>
<P>
German news agency DPA on Saturday quoted the Dutch newspaper
Haagsche Courant as reporting that the French government was
determined to veto the nomination of Duisenberg while Dutch Prime
Minister Wim Kok was most likely to do the same on the choice of
Trichet.
</P>
<P>
To break the deadlock, a third candidate seemed now to be the
only possible solution, the Dutch newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
