<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jamaican PM Urges More Investments in Education for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Jamaica's Prime Minister, P.J.
Patterson told the participants of the Second Summit of the
Americas opened here Saturday to help increase investment in
education in small and less developed nations of the Caribbean
region.
</P>
<P>
"Unless significant impetus is given to education now, in the
less developed economies, the Free Trade Area of the Americas
(FTAA) will result in entrenching the disparities which now exist
between the developed and under-developed states," Patterson said.
This would not achieve the FTAA's goal of a more prosperous, more
democratic, and more peaceful hemisphere, he added.
</P>
<P>
"From the perspective of the Caribbean and other small states,
the two issues of trade and education, in terms of the long-term
sustainability of our economies and the quality of the life of our
peoples, are inextricably linked," the Prime Minister emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The stronger economies are strong because of scale,
diversification, skills and significantly to an earlier and
sustained investment in education and training, he said. "Growth
and diversification of smaller economies will depend on the
ability of the people to benefit from knowledge-based industries,
and the use and export of intellectual capital, the application of
research to development, the creative use of the aesthetic
intelligences, as well as the application of science and
technology in ways, yet to be discovered," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Jamaican leader called for increased multilateral support
for education and hemispheric funding which is aimed to provide
assistance with setting of hemispheric standards, establishing
mechanisms of accreditation and equivalences and providing current
statistical data for governments and businesses within the
hemisphere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
