<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gaviria Says OAS to Undertake Reform After Santiago Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Cesar Gaviria, General Secretary
of the Organization of American States (OAS) said he considers to
undertake a process of reform and of the creation of a new
inter-American architecture at the OAS as a result of the Santiago
Summit.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the working session of the Second Summit of
the Americas opened here Saturday, Gaviria said the Santiago
Summit set forth a new and consistent political reality. In order
to make the OAS a useful and efficient instrument to carry out the
new tasks, "we are thinking of the Organization of tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
"We have a vision of the Organization carrying out its
theatrical role in the creation of inter-American law and as a
trustee of treaties and agreements; as a prime forum of
hemispheric political dialogue; as a center for exchanging
experiences and of designing communal or collective policies; as
responsible for building and maintaining hemispheric information
systems; as a tool of continental solidarity through its
cooperative projects," the OAS chief noted.
</P>
<P>
Forty months ago in Miami, where the First Summit of the
Americas was held, leaders of the 34 countries in the west
hemisphere ended a decades of isolationism, confrontation, and
distrust, abandoning the hostile language and a certain atavistic
pessionism that characterized the political and economic manner of
speaking, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted, there will be still a long way to go to
make the institution "a useful and efficient instrument" to carry
out the new tasks ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
