<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S., Jordan Partners for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said here Saturday that Jordan and the U.S. are
partners for peace and stability in the Mideast region and the
U.S. appreciates Jordan's role in helping solving regional issues.
</P>
<P>
"This visit is an opportunity for our countries to reaffirm
our shared goals for the future," said Cohen at a joint news
conference with Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali
following his talks with King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-U.S. partnership is based on the pursuit of peace
among Israel and Arab countries, said Cohen, who arrived here
Saturday from Turkey on a two-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's current tour will also take him to Egypt, Israel and
Greece before he returns home on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We both agree that the key for stability in the Middle East is
a just and lasting peace agreement between Israel and its
neighbors," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. defense secretary said the second important role of
the Jordanian-U.S. partnership is to contain Iraq from developing
into a regional power that will be a threat to the peace and
stability in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"We also both agree it is important to prevent Iraq from
attacking its neighbors again and from continuing to work on its
program to build deadly chemical and biological weapons," he
said.
</P>
<P>
As a sign of its appreciation of Jordan's fidelity to the
partnership, the U.S. "worked very hard to provide Jordan with its
defense requirements," said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
"We have tried to be completely responsive to Jordan's
security needs ... and the cooperation between Jordan and the
U.S. is very strong and productive," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also indicated that the U.S. will grant the kingdom
aircraft in the future, and that a thorough evaluation of its
security needs will be conducted soon.
</P>
<P>
Majali on his part confirmed the partnership between Jordan and
the U.S., saying the long-stalled Middle East peace process can
not be resumed without Washington's basic and pivotal role in its
capacity as one of the key sponsors of the process.
</P>
<P>
The role of Jordanian-U.S. partnership in saving the peace
process, particularly in the field of military cooperation, is
"great," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Majali, the U.S. granted Jordan 75 million
U.S. dollars in military aid out of a 225-million-dollar overall
aid package to the kingdom in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration is to maintain its aid at the same
level as in 1997. From 1990 to 1997, the U.S. provided Jordan a
total of 1.552 billion dollars worth of economic and military aid.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's visit to Jordan had been scheduled for the last quarter
of 1997, but was postponed due to Iraq's standoff with the United
Nations over weapons inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
